<FILEID>AP-NR-05-29-89 0012EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-IvyLeagueTrial     05-29 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ivy League Trial,0720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seeming Success Story Takes Tragic Turn</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUE MANNING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boy of the Year, high school honors
graduate, athletic standout, Harvard scholar. Jose Luis Razo was a
barrio youth who made good.
   Now he's standing trial for a string of armed robberies that
coincided with his college breaks or vacations _ and blaming drugs,
delusion and a boyhood friend for the holdups and the case against
him.
   Jurors must decide if Razo is a guilt-wracked victim of his
success or, as the prosecutor charges, a ``cocky liar'' who has
been ``taking people for a ride for a long time.''
   Razo, 22, is on trial in Orange County on 10 counts of robbery
and one of escape. The case is expected to go to the jury by next
week.
   He's also set to go on trial soon in Los Angeles County, where
he is charged with three counts of robbery and six of assault with
a deadly weapon.
   Razo moved to California with his family in the late 1960s. As a
youngster, he was an altar boy. Police describe him as a former
gang member, but family and friends remember him as a Boys Club
``Boy of the Year.''
   ``He went from a struggling background to the epitome of success
for a young man,'' said Richard Guthrie, director of the La Habra
Boys Club.
   At Servite High School, a Roman Catholic school in Anaheim, Razo
was an ``A'' student and standout football player wooed by over 60
colleges around the country when he graduated.
   He chose a scholarship to Harvard University, where Hispanics
represent only 4.7 percent of the student body.
   As a freshman in 1985, he set out to study psychology and talked
of becoming a lawyer.
   ``He always said, `Look how good I'm doing. I'm Mexican. I'm
trying to make it in a white world,''' his sister Martha said in
July 1987. ``He's out to prove to people that he's as smart as
anyone.''
   In December 1985, a masked man started robbing fast-food
restaurants, grocery stores and dairies in Southern California. The
holdups netted the gunman more than $27,000 and coincided with
trips Razo made to California.
   When Razo called police in June 1987 to say he had information
on an unrelated crime, he was questioned about the robberies.
   When pressed, he confessed.
   It wasn't Razo's first run-in with police. At 17, he was
convicted of petty theft. A few months later, he was charged with
assault, although that case was dismissed.
   His videotaped confession became the cornerstone of the robbery
prosecution. Motions to get the confession thrown out failed.
   In a jailhouse interview after his arrest, Razo said: ``I wasn't
taking money from anybody that really, really needed it. I did the
crime, I'll do the time.''
   About his life at Harvard, he said: ``I didn't fit. I was
confused.''
   Later, free on $100,000 bail, Razo claimed he used the stolen
money to help his poor family and needy friends. They said they
never saw it. In fact, his sister said: ``My mom always sent him
money. She wouldn't pay bills to send him money.''
   In court, Razo pleaded innocent and said he had confessed in a
drug-induced stupor during which he accepted blame for the crimes
because he felt guilty about being successful while his family and
friends were not.
   He testified that the holdups were committed by a childhood
friend and drug dealer, Richard Longoria. He said Longoria had
described the robberies to him in detail.
   ``In hindsight, I now see that I was feeling very guilty about
my Harvard experience, my comfortable lifestyle,'' Razo testified
Wednesday. ``I was feeling alienated from my family at home and
Mexicans in general.
   ``I wanted to be accepted in a normal, everyday type of way in
terms of the neighborhood and friends I had known. I was wanting to
truly identify with Richard Longoria.''
   Deputy District Attorney Ravi Mehta and Razo's attorney, John
Barnett, have been trying to locate Longoria. But Barnett said he
wasn't sure if Longoria's testimony could help the defense. Mehta
said it wouldn't make any difference.
</TEXT>
