<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Ireland-Politics     05-29 0146</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Ireland-Politics,0149</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Alliance Formed in Irish Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The country's two main opposition parties
have formed a pre-election alliance to try to prevent Prime
Minister Charles Haughey from winning his first outright
parliamentary majority.
   The Fine Gael and Labor parties, faring poorly in opinion polls
against Haughey's governing Fianna Fail party, announced during the
weekend that they were combining forces for the June 15 general
election.
   If elected, they pledged to cut income taxes, increase
investment in health services and reduce public borrowing from 5
percent to 3 percent of gross national product.
   Fianna Fail will form the first single-party majority government
since 1977 if its 50 percent-plus approval rating in recent opinion
polls is reflected in the election.
   Haughey, 63, has won and lost office twice, but has never led
his party to a majority in the Dail, or Parliament.
</TEXT>
