<FILEID>AP-NR-05-29-89 0015EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     05-29 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TROY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Employees at an elegant mall have not been
able to figure out why a duck chose a planter outside the complex
to prepare for motherhood, but they're making her comfortable as
she sits on her nine eggs.
   ``We have a layette all planned out, and a shower in the
works,'' said Mary Ellen Brigman, who works at Saks Fifth Avenue at
the Somerset Mall. ``And a makeover. After nine kids at once, she's
going to need it.''
   The duck has spent about a month at the mall sitting on her eggs.
   When the eggs hatch in about two or three weeks, the Humane
Society may move the duck and her brood to a nearby lake.
   No one is sure why the duck moved to the mall.
   ``Maybe she's a country duck who wants to be citified,'' said
Magda Marudas, a personnel supervisor for Saks. ``Or just a classy
duck.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The big cheese is back.
   The ``Belle of Wisconsin,'' a mammoth, 20-ton block of cheddar
cheese, has returned home after a yearlong tour of the United
States.
   The cheese _ measuring 20 feet long, 6 feet wide and 6 feet tall
and weighing 40,060 pounds _ arrived in Milwaukee this weekend
after touring 350 cities in 36 states.
   ``In the metropolitan areas, they didn't care much for it. There
was so much else going on,'' said Pat Patterson, 59, who drove the
Belle's custom-made semi-trailer truck some 55,000 miles in the
last year.
   ``But in the outlying areas and in the suburbs there was a real
good reaction, especially among the children,'' he said. ``Some of
them asked questions like `How much milk did it take?' or `How many
cows did it take?'''
   The Belle will begin a second tour of Wisconsin later this week
that will end at the State Fair in August. The block will then be
sliced into one-pound chunks and sold around the country.
   Created by cheesemaker Dave Simon, of Little Chute, in March
1988 and sponsored by the Wisconsin Milk Marketing Board, the Belle
was marketed as the largest block of cheese ever.
   Wisconsin is the No. 1 cheese producer in the country, with an
annual output of more than 1.9 billion pounds.
</TEXT>
