<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Evangelist Oral Roberts' son returned from a
seven-day singing tour in the Soviet Union saying the time is right
for preaching in the Soviet bloc.
   ``The Lord told my father some 20 years ago that the Soviet
Union and China would open for a brief time to the gospel, and then
the door would quickly close,'' Richard Roberts said last week. ``I
believe that time has arrived.
   ``I feel in my spirit that the gospel will flourish here almost
without repression because the Russians are going to have their
hands full,'' he said.
   The Soviet Union's National Jazz Society invited Roberts and a
group of 14 Oral Roberts University students on a singing tour
through the Soviet republics of Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GREENBRAE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Sen. S.I. Hayakawa was
hospitalized after complaining of breathing difficulties and
weakness, but tests failed to uncover any serious health problems,
hospital officials said.
   Hayakawa, 82, was admitted to Marin General Hospital on Friday.
He was in stable condition Sunday and was expected to be released
within a few days, said nursing supervisor Marilyn Snyder.
   Hayakawa gained recognition as a conservative in 1969 when as
acting president of San Francisco State University he called in
police to repress anti-war protests on campus. He was president of
the university until 1973.
   The semantics expert known for his trademark tam-o'-shanter won
his Senate seat as a Republican in 1976, and served one six-year
term.
   He lives in Mill Valley north of San Francisco.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joe Clark, the disciplinarian high school
principal portrayed in the movie ``Lean on Me,'' underwent surgery
to replace a heart valve and was in satisfactory condition,
hospital officials said.
   Clark, principal of Eastside High School in Paterson, was
recovering in the cardiac care unit of Beth Israel Hospital,
hospital spokesman Tom Casey said Sunday.
   Clark, 52, who gained national recognition for his
bat-and-bullhorn method of discipline at the school, was admitted
to the hospital Wednesday with a high fever, officials said.
   Surgery was necessary to remove bacteria from the heart valve
and prevent the infection from spreading to other organs, said
Clark's cardiologist, Dr. Sharlene Watts.
   One of Clark's aortic valves was replaced with an artificial
valve during four hours of surgery, Casey said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul Newman and Joanne Woodward will
spend about two months here later this year to make a film about
the lives of the Kansas City well-to-do in the years preceding
World War II.
   ``Mr. and Mrs. Bridge'' is based on Evan S. Connell's novels
``Mrs. Bridge'' and ``Mr. Bridge.''
   Director James Ivory, whose credits include ``A Room With A
View'' and ``A Passage to India,'' arrived Friday to scout
locations for the production, which is scheduled to begin filming
in August.
   Ivory said the $7 million film is relatively inexpensive by
Hollywood standards.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reclusive country music star Don
Williams says his new album is the first one he's wanted to talk
about in years.
   ``I don't know if I tried any harder on this one. But I will say
we had more fun in the studio than ever, which was delightful,''
Williams said recently.
   Williams gave 80 concerts in 1982, cut back to 50 in 1985, then
retreated altogether for 18 months to his 90-acre farm about 10
miles northwest of Nashville.
   ``I was feeling like, maybe it's time for me to hang it up. You
know, just forget it,'' Williams said.
   His new album, ``One Good Well,'' has already yielded a hit with
the title tune. Williams' other hits include ``The Shelter of Your
Eyes,'' ``We Should Be Together,'' and ```Til the Rivers All Run
Dry.''
   Williams' songs have been recorded by musicians as diverse as
Eric Clapton, Johnny Cash, Pete Townsend, Kenny Rogers and Charley
Pride.
</TEXT>
