<FIRST>r i AM-Argentina 1stLd-Writethru a0814 05-29 0674</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0814,0694</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Hand Out Food To Stop Looting</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New info Alfonsin speech on economic plans, more looting in
Rosasrio grafs 1-16. Pickup 6th graf pvs: In the industrial...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM H. HEATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Provincial authorities, political
parties and labor unions handed out free groceries to poor families
Sunday in an effort to stop the looting of food stores.
   Argentina has runaway inflation and food prices are soaring.
More than 50 cases of looting were reported last week in four of
the largest cities _ Buenos Aires, Cordoba, Rosaria and Mendoza.
   Edgardo Soto, Rosario's public safety director, said 10 food
markets were attacked by looters Sunday. No arrests were reported.
   Police elsewhere said the number of looting incidents had
diminished.
   Political uncertainty has fueled the economic crisis and
President Raul Alfonsin urged Argentines to support a package of
emergency measures designed to control an ``extremely dangerous and
cruelly damaging'' economic situation.
   Alfonsin announced the measures in a 35-minute televised address
Sunday night. They include exchange controls, tax increases and
cuts in government spending.
   His government is trying to deal with inflation that is expected
to exceed 60 percent in May alone, a plunge in the value of the
local currency that has lost 90 percent of its value in the last
three months and deteriorating salaries.
   Alfonsin called the economic measures ``absolutely necessary''
to ensure an orderly transfer of power from his administration to
that of President-elect Carlos Menem scheduled for Dec. 10.
   ``We are willing to modify some of our criteria'' to fit Menem's
plan, Alfonsin said.
   His Radical Civic Union lost elections May 14 to Menem's
Peronist Party.
   Alfonsin said the free monetary exchange system will be replaced
by one controlled by the government. He gave no details.
   Newspapers have suggested the Argentine austral will be pegged
at between 160 and 170 per dollar for import and export operations.
The dollar has topped 200 australs recently on the free exchange
market.
   Export taxes will be increased by 10 percent to a total of 30
percent for agricultural exports and 20 percent for industrial
exports, the president said.
   He said the government will cut spending and sign no new
contracts for public works, and radio and television stations
operated by the state will be privatized. Three of the nation's
five main television channels have been under government control
since 1974..
   Alfonsin also said travel by government officials will be
strictly limited and he will cancel a scheduled visit to France.
   The government will not set maximum prices for consumer goods
but will continue the policy under which prices may not be
increased without specific government approval, the president said.
   In the industrial city of Cordoba the provincial government
began distributing 10,000 rations daily of pasta, bread and milk in
``Operation Solidarity.''
   Provincial Social Affairs Minister Ruben Marti said the program
would continue until ``the financial-economic situation
stabilizes.'' He said the food was furnished from government stocks
and by political parties, labor unions and private businesses.
   Food stores in Cordoba were guarded by police and members of a
border guard unit called to special duty by Gov. Eduardo Angeloz.
   The provincial government said about 200 people had been
arrested in connection with least 40 cases of looting of
supermarkets and grocery stores.
   The United Left, a coalition of political parties in Cordoba,
accused provincial authorities of ``resorting to repression to halt
the reply that popular sectors have begun to give to the crisis,
mobilizing themselves to combat their misery.''
   The looting of markets began Tuesday in Cordoba and by Friday
had spread to other cities.
   The number of lootings had diminished by Saturday but police
reported several incidents in the Buenos Aires metropolitan area.
   The newspaper La Nacion reported Sunday that from May 26, 1988,
to the same date this year the price of 2.2 pounds of potatoes went
up 3,233 percent and there were increases of 900 percent for 2.2
pounds of flank steak and 2,079 percent for a dozen eggs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
