<SECOND>PM-Summit-Leaders,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cast of Characters for NATO Summit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are the leaders of the 16 NATO
countries and the alliance head gathering for the NATO summit today
and Tuesday:
   _NATO secretary-general and summit chairman Manfred Woerner, 54,
a former West German defense minister who heads NATO's 1,600-member
international staff.
   _Belgian Prime Minister Wilfried Martens, 53, a Christian
Democrat who has led eight coalition governments since 1979.
   _Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney, 50, a Conservative in
office since September 1984.
   _Danish Prime Minister Poul Schlueter, 60, a Conservative who
has led a three-party minority coalition since June 1988.
   _French President Francois Mitterrand, 72, the Socialist Party
leader of France since 1981.
   _German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, 59, a Christian Democrat who has
led a center-right coalition since 1982.
   _Greek Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou, 70, leader of the
Panhellenic Socialist Movement, who came to power in 1981.
   _Icelandic Prime Minister Steingrimur Hermannsson, 61, a
Progressive Party member who has led a three-party coalition since
last September.
   _Italian Prime Minister Ciriaco De Mita, 61, a Christian
Democrat who came to office last month atop a five-party coalition.
   _Luxembourg Prime Minister Jacques Santer, 52, a Christian
Democrat leading a center-left coalition.
   _Dutch Prime Minister Ruud Lubbers, 50, a Christian Democrat
heading a caretaker government in the Netherlands since early May.
   _Norwegian Prime Minister Gro Harlem Brundtland, 50, who heads a
minority Labor government with support from the Socialist Left
party.
   _Portuguese Prime Minister Anibal Cavaco Silva, 50, a Social
Democrat who has led Portugal's first-ever absolute parliamentary
majority since July 1987.
   _Spanish Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez Marquez, 47, a Socialist
in office since 1982.
   _Turkish Prime Minister Turgut Ozal, 62, a member of the
Motherland Party in power since 1983.
   _British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, 64, a Conservative
who has just marked her 10th year in office.
   _U.S. President George Bush, 64, a Republican sworn into office
last January after eight years as Ronald Reagan's vice president.
</TEXT>
