<FILEID>AP-NR-05-29-89 0052EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-NATOMissiles     05-29 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NATO Missiles,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Officials Say No Rush to Resolve Missile Dispute</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. officials on the eve of the NATO summit
reiterated the administration's belief that an agreement on
conventional forces should take precedence over reducing the number
the number of short-range nuclear weapons in West Germany and the
Warsaw Pact.
   But the officials, Defense Secretary Dick Cheney and Secretary
of State James A. Baker III, also said they believed the alliance
could have a successful summit without a resolution of the nuclear
weapons issue.
   ``Short-range nuclear forces are an essential part of the
deterrent,'' Cheney said on CBS-TV's ``Face the Nation,'' a Sunday
news program. ``They ought to stay there while we focus on
conventional armaments. After we've dealt with the conventional
problem, then we can come back and talk about short-range forces.
   ``I don't think there's any magic about having to resolve it at
the end of May of 1989.''
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl has been warning against a delay in talks
between the superpowers over the nuclear weapons with ranges of 300
miles or less.
   Baker, appearing on NBC-TV's ``Meet the Press,'' said President
Bush is willing to negotiate with the Soviet Union on reducing the
number of nuclear weapons, but he does not feel any pressure to
resolve the problem during this week's 16-nation meeting.
   ``The president has already acknowledged at least the principle
of negotiations, although he feels very, very strongly that before
you can talk about that or get into that, you need to see a
conventional forces agreement,'' Baker said.
   The United States has pushed for modernization of the Lance
missiles while West Germany has urged superpower negotiations to
reduce the weapons, located on German soil.
   U.S. officials now say they are amenable to talks with the
Soviets at an unspecified date, but the United States and Britain
still say those negotiations should not take place while the Warsaw
Pact nations remain superior in conventional forces. The dispute
has created a rift within the NATO alliance.
   Kohl on Saturday said U.S.-Soviet negotiations on the
short-range weapons ``cannot be postponed into the distant future.
We are the front-line country in NATO. It is clear that we should
be speaking up for our interests.''
   National security adviser Brent Scowcroft, interviewed on
ABC-TV's ``This Week with David Brinkley,'' said elimination of the
short-range weapons would undermine NATO strategy because the
weapons ``are there, in part, to make up for the conventional
imbalance that has existed since the foundation of NATO.''
   While the Western alliances's short-range missile launchers are
based primarily on West German soil, the Warsaw Pact has
short-range weapons in East Germany, Poland, Czechoslovakia and
Hungary.
   According to Western estimates, the Soviet Union has 1,450
short-range nuclear missile launchers while NATO has 88. The
Soviets are said to have some 3,000 missiles of various types that
could be used on their launchers, while NATO has 700 Lance
single-warhead missiles.
   Overall, according to NATO figures, the Soviets have 6,260
nuclear artillery systems compared to 2,700 for the alliance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
