<FIRST>r w PM-Coelho     05-29 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coelho,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coelho Calls on Bush to Stop `Partisan and Petty Politics'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Democratic Whip Tony Coelho, who plans
to resign from Congress rather than face an ethics investigation,
says it's up to President Bush to stop ``partisan and petty
politics'' being practiced by some Republicans.
   Coelho spoke in an interview with CBS television on Sunday, one
day after announcing he will leave Congress on June 15.
   Bush is playing ``good cop'' in talking about cooperation and
bipartisanship, while Republican campaign officials are playing
``bad cops,'' the California Democrat said.
   ``If he wants to do away with the partisan and petty politics
that he talks about, then Mr. President, stand up and say so,''
Coelho said, adding the president should ``stand up and fire those
people who are unwilling to do what you want to have done.''
   Coelho said Republicans wanted him to stay in office to face
ethical questions about his $100,000 junk bond deal in 1986.
   ``The biggest disappointment they have is that they wanted me to
stay in for the next two years so that they could use me as a
vehicle to destroy my party and my causes from going forward,'' the
California Democrat said, according to a transcript of a portion of
the interview that was not broadcast. ``I took that away from them.
... I know what I'm doing.''
   ``Do we make mistakes? Yes we do. Did I make a mistake? Yes I
did. I'm willing to pay for it,'' Coelho said during the broadcast
interview.
   Coelho has steadfastly insisted he did nothing wrong _ aside
from some reporting errors _ in the junk bond transaction, which
was financed without him having to put up any of his own money.
   Before Saturday, Coelho was planning to run for House majority
leader to replace Rep. Tom Foley, who is expected to become speaker
upon the expected resignation of Speaker Jim Wright of Texas, who
also faces ethical questions.
   Coelho told CBS that he believes House GOP Whip Newt Gingrich of
Georgia is trying to ``create a political agenda to try to get
control of the United States House of Representatives.
   ``Newt has said the only way for Republicans to get control is
to destroy the institution, tear it down and then to rebuild it,''
Coelho said. ``I don't think the American public wants that.''
</TEXT>
