<DOCNO> AP890529-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-29-89 0110EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Salvador-Military     05-29 0678</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador-Military,0700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Split Military Narrowly Avoids Clash</HEAD>
<UNK>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE ^Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The armed forces, deeply
divided over who should direct the war against leftist rebels,
narrowly avoided an internal clash last week before agreeing on a
compromise defense minister, according to well-informed sources.
   The discord has been only cosmetically overcome, and the rivalry
will again come to a head within months after a new government
takes office Thursday, the sources said this weekend.
   Most of the military, diplomatic and political sources consulted
in the matter spoke on condition of anonymity. But outgoing
president Jose Napoleon Duarte and an army colonel acknowledged
publicly that an atmosphere of crisis prevailed last week during
the high command's deliberations.
   The air force, whose commander was one of two top candidates to
head the Defense Ministry, halted ground support operations at
midweek and limited itself to evacuating wounded, sources said.
   They said some air force officers had expected armor-backed army
troops to move on Ilopango Air Base, the air force headquarters,
last Thursday.
   Maneuvering for the Defense Ministry post reportedly included
harsh mutual recriminations between air force chief Gen. Rafael
Bustillo and the other top candidate, Col. Rene Emilio Ponce, head
of the joint chiefs of staff.
   In a reported shouting match, they accused each other of
fostering or ignoring corruption in their respective ranks.
   The high command finally agreed that Gen. Humberto Larios,
currently vice-minister of defense, should take over as minister
after President-elect Alfredo Cristiani is sworn in Thursday.
   Cristiani heads the rightist Republican Nationalist Alliance, or
Arena.
   Larios will replace Gen. Eugenio Vides Casanova, who reportedly
will go to West Germany as military attache.
   Cristiani, who preferred Bustillo for the post but ceded at the
prospect of internal battle, has accepted Larios, at least
temporarily, the sources said.
   According to the constitution, the president names his Cabinet.
But civilian authority in El Salvador remains conditioned on
military approval and tutelage, especially in defense matters.
   The confrontation is not a simple showdown between the air force
and army. If it were, the army, with its superior force, would have
succeeded in imposing Ponce.
   Several key army colonels with command of troops back Bustillo,
the sources said. Those who back the airman contend he is more of a
natural leader, more of a nationalist and has greater resolve than
Ponce to do what is necessary to win the 9-year-old civil war.
   Bustillo is considered a virulently anti-communist hardliner
relatively unconcerned about international criticism for human
rights abuses.
   Ponce is seen as an exponent of continuing the same, or slightly
modified, Low Intensity Warfare strategy pursued to date.
   Despite more than $800 million in U.S. military aid this decade,
the 56,000-strong armed forces has been unable to defeat an
insurgent force estimated to number 7,000 combatants and 14,000
militia members.
   The war has claimed the lives of an estimated 70,000 people,
most of them civilians.
   The sources said the U.S. Embassy, which wields considerable
leverage in El Salvador, staunchly backed Ponce then proposed
Larios as a compromise.
   ``In all institutions, there is an element of institutional
crisis when the government changes,'' Duarte told reporters
Saturday of rumors of the military turmoil. ``Everyone tries to
ensure his post. This means that at the distinct levels of the
armed forces, there are expressions of defense of interests in the
effort to conform to the change.''
   Col. Benjamin Canjura, commander of a provincial garrison, told
Radio YSU on Friday that tension was high in the military over the
defense ministry fight.
   Opponents of Arena contend Cristiani, a suave U.S.-educated
businessman, is little more than a palatable facade on what they
say is a neo-fascist organization. They claim he is subordinate to
hardliners.
   The incumbent Christian Democrats used the slogan ``Cristiani
doesn't run things,'' prior to the March 19 presidential election,
in which Duarte's party was trounced.
   Canjura said that despite Cristiani's acceptance of Larios other
high-ranking Arena officials insist on Bustillo.
   ``This a chance for Cristiani to show if he runs things or
not,'' said Canjura.
</TEXT>
