<DOCNO> AP890529-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-29-89 0241EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Uruguay     05-29 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Uruguay,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Batlle Wins Colorado Party Presidential Nomination</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Batlle is cq throughout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL GIANELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTEVIDEO, Uruguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Jorge Batlle, whose family has
provided Uruguay with three presidents, won the presidential
nomination for the majority faction of the governing Colorado Party
in a primary election.
   With 95 percent of the votes counted, the party announced that
Batlle had tallied 171,117 votes or 54.9 percent on Sunday,
compared with 124,218, or 39.85 percent for Vice President Enrique
Tarigo.
   Batlle, 62, will represent the party's faction in the Nov. 26
election. The same faction had backed President Julio Sanguinetti,
whose five-year term expires on March 1, 1990. Sanguinetti took
over in 1985 after 12 years of military rule.
   Under Uruguayan law, individual parties may field more than one
candidate for the presidency.
   Battle stressed that Uruguay take a ``qualitative leap forward''
through liberalization of its economy. He also proposed sale of
Uruguay's gold reserves to obtain funds to pay part of the
country's foreign debt.
   Uruguay's $6.1 billion foreign debt and interest payments of
$300 million per year are largely responsible for the deficit and
an annual inflation rate of 79 percent, Batlle said. The country
has $1 billion in gold reserves.
   Batlle's family has a long tradition in Uruguayan politics. His
father, Luis Batlle, great uncle, Jose Batlle, and great
grandfather, Gen. Lorenzo Batlle, all were presidents.
   Batlle will join seven other candidates already selected for the
race to succeed Sanguinetti.
   They include former President Jorge Pacheco Areco, who will
represent a minority faction of the Colorado Party, and three
candidates for the leading opposition National Party, Senators
Alberto Zumaran, Carlos Julio Pereyra and Luis A. Lacalle.
   The candidate for the leftist coalition Broad Front will be
retired army Gen. Liber Seregni. The Peoples' Party for Government,
a social democrat group, will be represented by Sen. Hugo Batalla
and the Green-Ecology Party by Rodolfo Talice, a 90-year-old
specialist on animal behavior.
</TEXT>
