<FILEID>AP-NR-05-29-89 0316EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-HongKong-China     05-29 0641</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hong Kong-China,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>Massive Rally Backs China's Pro-Democracy Movement</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LIU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The suppression of liberal forces in China has
further unnerved Hong Kong over its future under Chinese rule,
triggering massive demonstrations and uncharacteristic political
activism.
   In largest protest march in this British colony's history, what
police estimated to be estimated 500,000 people rallied Sunday in
support of China's pro-democracy protesters.
   Police said the crowd exceeded the estimated 400,000 who
demonstrated on May 21 protest Chinese Premier Li Peng's
declaration of martial law in Beijing. Organizers said 1.5 million
people attended Sunday's rally.
   Hong Kong reverts to Chinese sovereignty in 1997, and its
residents have become increasingly nervous over the prospect of
Communist Chinese rule.
   A poll conducted by the conservative South China Morning Post
newspaper reported that one-third of the territory's 5.7 million
people hope to emigrate before the takeover.
   China has promised to preserve the territory's freewheeling
socioeconomic lifestyle for 50 years under a ``one country, two
systems'' concept that would allow capitalism to exist under
communism in a government run by Hong Kong people without Chinese
interference.
   Hong Kong residents have long been skeptical about the Chinese
promises, and Li's decision to slap martial law on Beijing has
deepened their anxiety.
   ``I believe that to call out the troops to handle a peaceful
demonstration by students does seem to be heavy-handed,'' said Dame
Lydia Dunn, senior member of the Executive Council, which functions
as a government Cabinet.
   Eric Hotung, a fourth-generation Hong Kong business magnate,
said Britain and China have repeatedly said Hong Kong's future
autonomy was assured in a Sino-British agreement signed in 1984.
   ``But (the people of Hong Kong) have also seen, and seen with
the greatest clarity, how indifferent the leaders in Beijing are
capable of being towards the legitimate aspirations of their own
people,'' said Hotung, whose grandfather, Sir Robert Hotung, was
among the first Chinese knighted by Britain.
   Community leaders and newspapers say a Basic Law document, under
which China will govern Hong Kong, should be strengthened to
safeguard the territory's autonomy.
   The document, drafted by a committee of Hong Kong and Chinese
delegates appointed by China, is to be presented to China's
congress for enactment next year.
   Demonstrations to support the pro-democracy movement in China
have been held daily for more than a week. Sunday's march lasted
eight hours, and the protesters included parents with babies,
students, elderly citizens and merchants.
   Chanting ``Long live democracy!'' and ``Support Beijing
students!'' the crowd began their march in a downtown business
district before ending their rally in a park.
   Banners of support were hung from a number of buildings,
including the pro-Beijing Ta Kung Pao newspaper.
   ``China and Hong Kong have the same fate,'' proclaimed one
banner. ``We need democracy for a better tomorrow.''
   Hong Kong's population is 98 percent Chinese. About two-thirds
are refugees from China or their descendants.
   In Taiwan, the Nationalists _ who claim to be the legitimate
rulers of all China _ have condemned the Chinese attempts to
suppress the pro-democracy movement, and President Lee Teng-hui has
instructed government officials to recommend ``effective measures''
that could be taken to help the students.
   But critics say this would take time, and newspapers, scholars
and citizens say the government should have moved faster.
   Chang Chun-hung, secretary general of the opposition Democratic
Progressive Party, said the Nationalists failed to respond
effectively because ``they neither have the capability nor the
desire to return to the mainland.''
   Wu Yen-huan, 79, a legislator from the governing Nationalist
Party, said that if President Chiang Kai-shek, who led the defeated
Nationalists to Taiwan in 1949, was still alive, he would have sent
troops across the Taiwan Strait to help students on the mainland
who are championing democracy. Chiang died in 1975.
   ``Times are different now,'' he lamented.
</TEXT>
