<HEAD>Dollar Strengthens, Stocks Fall</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with dollar, stock close; pickup
4th graf, `Currency dealers...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose sharply against the Japanese yen
Monday, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost ground.
   The dollar closed at 142.88 yen, up 2.48 yen from last Friday's
close of 140.40 yen, after trading in a range of 142.65-143.18 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained
153.57 points for a record-high 34,191.62-point close Friday, shed
30.79 points, or 0.09 percent, to close at 34,160.83.
   Currency dealers said the dollar's strength followed its rally
in the Sydney market, which opened earlier than Tokyo.
   ``The dollar's bullishness is largely due to speculative
actions,'' said a dealer at a major Japanese commercial bank,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   He said the Bank of Japan sold about $300 million Monday morning
in an attempt to break the rising dollar. Officials at the central
bank declined to comment.
   Dealers also said a report that West German monetary authorities
are unlikely to hike key interest rates contributed to the dollar's
bullishness.
   Securities dealers said the Nikkei index opened higher, but the
sharp gain of the dollar against the Japanese yen discouraged
further buying of shares.
</TEXT>
