<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stocks Dip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose sharply against the Japanese yen in
Tokyo today, causing stock prices to dip, dealers said.
   The dollar ended trading at 142.88 yen, up 2.48 yen from
Friday's close of 140.40 yen. After opening sharply higher at
142.75 yen, the U.S. currency ranged between 142.65 and 143.18 yen
during the day.
   ``Market expectations that the West German central bank will not
raise its interest rates encouraged dollar-buying,'' said a dealer
at a Japanese commercial bank.
   Reports in European newspapers that the West German central bank
is unlikely to raise its interest rates boosted dollar-buying in
Sydney and then in Tokyo today.
   ``The dollar's bullishness is largely due to speculation,'' said
another dealer at a major Japanese commercial bank, who also spoke
on condition of anonymity.
   Dealers said the Bank of Japan sold about $800 million today in
an attempt to break the rising dollar. Officials at the central
bank declined to comment.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which gained 153.57 points Friday, shed 30.79
points or 0.09 percent, closing at 34,160.83.
   The index moved up in early trading, but the sharp gain of the
dollar against the Japanese yen discouraged further share buying,
traders said.
   ``The market is ready for a new rally, but unstable exchange
rates are ruining it,'' said Ichitaro Watanabe, a dealer at Nikko
Securities Co. ``We have to wait until the yen-dollar rates settle
down to launch any campaigns.''
