<FIRST>r a PM-PipelineExplosion     05-29 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pipeline Explosion,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pipeline Lawyer Says `Little Town' Trying to Block Commerce</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN BERNARDINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city is accusing the operators
of a pipeline that exploded of pushing to restore the flow of
gasoline without enough thought for the safety of local residents.
   Two people were killed and 15 homes were burned when the 14-inch
line blew up Thursday in the same area where a runaway freight
train jumped the tracks and demolished a row of houses May 12.
Speculation is the train damaged the line.
   The parent company of the locally based Calnev Pipe Line Co.
announced Sunday the damaged pipeline will be rebuilt under tougher
standards. The company had obtained a court order Saturday barring
the city from ordering that the line be rerouted.
   Charles P. Diamond, an attorney for Calnev, complained that San
Bernardino, a city of about 120,000, is ``a little town trying to
take on interstate commerce.''
   The city, in turn, accused Calnev of insensitivity.
   ``Their entire attitude ever since the disaster occurred on
Thursday has been one of callousness toward the people of San
Bernardino, and they've been very obvious that their one concern is
to get their petroleum products flowing again,'' City Attorney
James Penman said.
   Penman said the city had asked to have the line move west of the
railroad track, under a dry river bed, but company officials
refused because of the cost.
   While the city cannot get Calnev to change the route of the
line, Penman said U.S. District Judge David Williams rewrote a
proposed restraining order to remove language that would have
barred the city from interfering with reopening the line, an option
the city is considering.
   The pipeline carries gasoline, diesel and jet fuel from a tank
farm in nearby Colton, several miles from the blast site, to
southern Nevada, supplying the Las Vegas Valley with 90 percent of
its fuel.
   Gsoline is being trucked to the desert resort while the line is
repaired.
   ``We believe that the best possible way to repair this pipeline
is to not only replace ... but also to bury it 100 percent deeper
than required by regulation to a depth of six feet,'' said Robert
Claypoole, president of Chicago-based GATX Terminals Corp, which
owns Calnev.
   ``To make any major changes in the routing of the line
additionally would cause a six- to eight-week interruption of
service,'' he said.
   Claypoole said the pipe will be tested by forcing water through
it at pressure 125 percent greater than normal operating pressure.
The hydrostatic test wasn't performed when the pipe was declared
safe following the derailment.
   William Pugh of the National Transportation Safety Board said
federal investigators plan to examine an additional 800 to 1,000
feet of the pipeline and conduct metallurgical tests on train parts
embedded in the earth near the line.
   About 270 people remain displaced from 70 homes damaged in the
fire, according to police Cpl. John Waterhouse.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
