<FIRST>r a PM-EvangelicalImmigrants     05-29 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Evangelical Immigrants,0403</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Union Evangelical Emigrating as Jews</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Evangelical Christians are getting exit visas from
the Soviet Union by pretending to be Jews wanting to go to Israel,
according to a report that says many end up settling in western
Massachusetts.
   Between 300 and 400 Soviet Pentecostals have settled in the
area, The Boston Globe reported today.
   The Slavic Pentecostal Church in West Springfield had seven
members 18 months ago. Today it is has 250, and three families are
living in the church basement.
   The Rev. Pawel Lubanski, pastor of the church, said he and his
wife try to find jobs, food, housing and transportation for the
immigrants, most of whom do not speak English when they arrive.
   It is virtually impossible for Soviet Christians to immigrate to
the United States, so Evangelicals pretend to be Jews wishing to go
to Israel, officials said.
   Soviet officials are said to look the other way because they
want to get rid of the Pentecostals while claiming only Jews seek
exit visas.
   ``Because of the way they get out, we never know when or how
many will show up,'' Lubanski said. Once a community has been
established in the United States, such as the one in West
Springfield, word spreads among those in the Soviet Union.
   ``It's an open secret that Christians are emigrating with Jewish
visas,'' said Serge Duss, Soviet refugee coordinator for World
Relief, an arm of the 15 million-member National Association of
Evangelicals.
   ``It's convenient to everyone. The real problems start once the
refugees, Jew and Christian alike, reach Vienna.''
   The case of each Soviet Union emigrant hoping to come to the
United States is evaluated individually before refugee status is
granted. Emigrants wait an average of 84 days in Vienna or Rome.
   Duss said 10,000 to 12,000 Jews and 2,200 Pentecostals are
awaiting processing in those cities. More than 5,000 Soviet Jews
and Christians are awaiting appeals after being denied refugee
status by the United States.
   The 47 Russian-speaking students in West Springfield public
schools have bilingual teachers for most subjects, said John
Rosenberg, assistant to the superintendent for curriculum and
programs.
   ``They've mixed right in and have been accepted 100 percent by
the other kids. They have formed very strong fireendships. They
learn English very quickly. In about a year, they are conversant,''
Rosenberg said.
</TEXT>
