<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     05-29 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was higher in Europe late this morning.
Foreign currency dealers said trading was light because of the
Memorial Day holiday in the United States and the British bank
holiday.
   Gold prices fell.
   Dealers said they were surprised by the dollar's rebound
following a round of coordinated central bank intervention on
Friday which, for the first time in weeks, included the Deutsche
Bundesbank.
   ``An upward correction was in the offing, but this is a bit
strong,'' said one dealer at a European bank in Frankfurt.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 2.48 yen to a closing 142.88 yen. Later, in
Europe, it was quoted at 142.53 yen.
   Other dollar rates in Europe at midmorning compared with late
Friday in London:
   _2.0090 West German marks, up from 1.9675
   _1.7345 Swiss francs, up from 1.7155
   _6.8030 French francs, up from 6.6625
   _2.2663 Dutch guilders, up from 2.2150
   _1,451.00 Italian lire, up from 1,421.75
   _1.2035 Canadian dollars, unchanged
   In Europe, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.57 to buy one pound, compared with $1.5922 dollars late Friday
in London.
   Bullion markets were closed in London for the bank holiday, but
in Zurich the bid price for gold was $363.20 a troy ounce, down
from $364.50 late Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 97 cents to close at a bid
$363.16.
</TEXT>
