<FIRST>r a PM-HomeStudios     05-29 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Home Studios,0631</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigation May Lead To Closure of Home Studios</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A recording industry group is campaigning to
restrict the use of home studios for musical production, a
development that some producers and musicians like Frank Zappa find
ominous.
   Efforts to shut down music producer Chas Sanford's home studio _
where the likes of Chicago, Rod Stewart and Stevie Nicks have
recorded _ could affect thousands of Hollywood creative people who
work out of their homes.
   The crackdown is in response to complaints about violations of
city zoning ordinances that prohibit commercial use of residential
property.
   ``If you look at the way they're applying this zoning concept,
that no one can do anything commercial in their house, you'd shut
Hollywood down,'' said Zappa, who has recorded his indiosyncratic
material for years at a studio in his Laurel Canyon home.
   ``Strictly speaking, other than a situation where they
(home-based workers) are immediately adjoining a commercial zone,
it's not a permitted use,'' said Frank Eberhard, the city's chief
zoning administrator. ``But unless there's a complaint, there's not
a real heavy enforcement of those rulings.''
   Sanford alleged that a fledgling trade group, the Hollywood
Association of Recording Professionals, is responsible for the
investigation into his studio, not his neighbors.
   ``They think everyone should be forced to go to their studios to
work. I don't think I should be told where I have to go and be
creative,'' Sanford said. ``It's a misuse of the law when a rival
studio 20 miles from my house _ not my next door neighbor _ can go
to the zoning commission and evoke the law to put someone out of
business.''
   Sanford contended that if artists are prohibited from working
out of their homes it could have a negative impact on the recording
industry.
   ``If these guys force everyone not to be able to work out of
their homes, there would only be $500,000 recording budgets,'' he
said. ``None of the new bands would be able to legally do stuff out
of their houses, which is where they all start.''
   But Buddy Brundo, owner of Conway Recording Studios, said the
commercial studios only want to target people who rent out home
studios, not musicians who work in their own homes.
   ``We're not talking about artist studios. We're talking about
people who build studios in their houses for hire,'' Brundo said.
``This guy (Sanford) built a studio for hire, period.''
   Sanford denied he runs a studio-for-hire business. He said that
in the 2{ years since he moved into the house he has rented it out
for a total of four sessions lasting 15 days, and those artists
were his friends.
   Many top recording artists have built studios in their homes.
Tom Petty recorded his ``Southern Accents'' album in the basement
studio of his Encino home, Van Halen recorded two albums at the
home studio of guitarist Eddie Van Halen and Dave Stewart of the
Eurythmics has done extensive recording at his home.
   Studio owners complained that state-of-the-art studio's such as
Sanford's give them an unfair advantage of not having to comply
with zoning regulations.
   ``We're playing by the rules and they're not,'' said Allen
Sides, owner of Ocean Way recording, which operates studios in
Hollywood and Sherman Oaks. ``If they want to compete on the same
basis, I don't think any of us have any complaints.
   ``But if they're going to operate and not pay 1.5 percent of
their gross in business tax, not pay proper state Board of
Equalization taxes, not pay proper overtime for their employees and
have health insurance plans and have handicapped bathrooms and all
the things that we have to do, it's a different story.''
</TEXT>
