<FIRST>r a PM-CruiseTest     05-29 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cruise Test,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Test Puts Cruise Missile Over Florida, Alabama, Back To Eglin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EGLIN AIR FORCE BASE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Navy Tomahawk cruise missile
launched from the Gulf of Mexico successfully completed a 450-mile
test flight over Florida and Alabama, a Department of Defense
spokesman said.
   The land-attack missile was launched at about 9:15 a.m. EDT
Sunday from a submarine under way in the Gulf and was recovered
after making a parachute landing in Eglin's test range, said Bob
Holsapple of the Cruise Missile Project.
   ``Tomahawks are known as the most-accurate (missiles) in the
world today and with a conventional, land-attack (configuration)
you can launch one from off the coast of Washington, D.C., and put
it inside Atlanta stadium through either goal post,'' Holsapple
said by phone from Fort Walton Beach.
   Cruise missiles can be launched from sea or air and can carry
nuclear or conventional warheads. The missile used in Sunday's test
was unarmed, said Holsapple.
   Because the jet-powered weapon was recovered by parachute,
rather than crash landing into its target as a live weapon would,
it can be refurbished, probably at a cost of $100,000 to $300,000.
A new missile would cost about $1.3 million, he said.
   Cruise missiles can fly up to 1,500 miles, depending on the
warhead.
</TEXT>
