<FIRST>r a PM-Missionaries     05-29 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Missionaries,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bodies of Slain Missionaries Returned to Salt Lake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bodies of two Mormon missionaries
gunned down by suspected terrorists in Bolivia last week have been
returned to Utah for burial.
   Cardboard-covered coffins containing the bodies of Todd Ray
Wilson, 20, and Jeffrey Brent Ball, 20, were lowered from a Delta
jetliner at Salt Lake International Airport Sunday as members of
the Ball family and Mormon Church officials looked on.
   The caskets were transported by hearse to two funeral homes. The
slain missionaries will be buried Tuesday.
   M. Russell Ballard, a member of the church's Quorum of the
Twelve Apostles, comforted Ball's mother, Lois, as other family
members locked arms.
   Ballard later expressed the church's ``deepest feelings of
trauma and sadness'' over the killings and vowed that the faith's
missionary program would continue in South America and around the
world.
   The church has 37,500 missionaries overseas.
   ``We express our deepest love and concern and sympathy to the
families of the victims,'' Ballard said.
   Wilson and Ball were shot down last Wednesday as they returned
to their apartment in La Paz. One of the missionaries died
immediately, the other en route to a hospital.
   A statement distributed to La Paz newspapers claimed
responsibility for the attack on behalf of the Zarate Willka Armed
Liberation Front, a group named for a 19th century Indian
revolutionary in Bolivia.
   Ballard said church officials understood that the FBI was
working with Bolivian authorities to find out ``who did this and
why ... and why two Mormon missionaries would be the target.''
   Until more answers are forthcoming, church officials have
confined nearly 400 missionaries in Bolivia to their apartments and
have advised mission presidents around the world to be ``careful
and wise.''
</TEXT>
