<DOCNO> AP890529-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-29-89 0843EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i BC-ArmsControl-Numbers     05-29 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Arms Control-Numbers,360</SECOND>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are details of the conventional arms
control proposal President Bush announced at the NATO summit
conference Monday:
   1. Limits on tanks, armored troop carriers and artillery pieces
by the NATO allies and the Soviet bloc, ceilings already proposed
by the West. Bush said his plan would seek to ``lock in Eastern
acceptance'' of the Western limits of 20,000 tanks, 28,000 armored
troop carriers and 16,500 to 24,000 artillery pieces, the precise
number depending on how those weapons are defined.
   Once the weapons are cut, they would be destroyed. The White
House said that would ``oblige the East to destroy tens of
thousands of weapons systems,'' in order to eliminate its wide
margin in those arms.
   According to NATO, the West has 16,424 main battle tanks and the
Warsaw Pact has 51,500 heavy tanks, with announced cuts to reduce
that number to 39,500.
   2. Reductions by each side in land-based combat airplanes and
helicopters to levels 15 percent below the current NATO level.
Those limits would apply from the Atlantic to the Ural Mountains.
Including those weapons would expand the conventional arms talks,
something the Soviet Union has sought.
   According to NATO, the Western alliance now has about 2,400
combat helicopters in active units, while the Warsaw Pact nations
have 3,700. There are nearly 4,000 combat aircraft in NATO and
about 8,250 in the Eastern bloc alliance, which has announced plans
to cut that number to 7,320.
   Under the Bush plan, the affected aircraft would be destroyed.
   3. The United States would make a 20 percent cut in its combat
manpower in Europe, to about 275,000, and that would become the
ceiling for Soviet forces stationed in other eastern European
nations. That manpower ceiling would require the Soviets to reduce
their forces in Eastern Europe by about 325,000. The withdrawn
troops would be demobilized.
   4. Both sides would accelerate the timetable for reaching an
agreement on conventional forces in Europe and for implementing the
resultant cuts. Bush said there should be agreement within six
months to a year, with the reductions to be effective by 1992 or
1993. The Soviet Union has set a 1997 target date for agreement..
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890529-0059 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-29-89 0856EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SouthKorea     05-29 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Korea,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Major Shake-Up of South Korean Government Expected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Roh Tae-woo will shuffle his
Cabinet to quell public anger over government mishandling of labor
unrest and friction with communist North Korea, officials said
today.
   The prime minister, the head of the nation's main intelligence
agency and the home, labor and construction ministers were among
those who may be replaced, the officials said. All major Seoul
newspapers carried reports of the expected shake-up.
   The reports surfaced as a hunger strike by 300 radical students
entered a fourth full day today. The protesters are calling for
Roh's resignation.
   Many of the hunger strikers at the Roman Catholic Myongdong
Cathedral appeared weak and exhausted. Riot police ringed the
cathedral but made no move to intervene.
   In the southern provincial capital of Kwangju, violent protests
broke out today when riot police blocked a march by 5,000 radical
students calling for Roh to step down, the South Korean news agency
Yonhap reported. No details were immediately available.
   The radical students lack public support because of their
extremist views.
   Government officials said they expected a major Cabinet shuffle
in the next weeks to give Roh's administration a new look. Senior
ministers and Prime Minister Kang Young-hoon were to take the blame
for recent violent unrest, the officials said on condition of
anonymity.
   ``Cabinet members to be replaced have not been decided, but it
is highly possible that the shuffle will affect many posts,'' one
official said.
   Roh, who won presidential elections in 1987, is unhappy that
ministers have failed to win public confidence, officials said. The
president believes the administration appears ineffective and needs
a new, stronger image, they said.
   In South Korea, periodic Cabinet shuffles spare the president
from taking responsibility for government failures. But Cabinet
ministers have little authority, and the presidency exacts full
control over the government.
   Park Seh-jik, head of the main intelligence agency, is being
blamed for the security forces' failure to stop dissident leader
Moon Ik-hwan visiting the communist North in March. Moon's visit
led to a confrontation between the Seoul government and dissidents
who seek unification of Korea. He was arrested on his return and
will be tried as a North Korean agent.
   Home Minister Lee Han-dong may be blamed for the threatened
resignation in April of thousands of police officers after an
opposition lawmaker slapped a top police commander, the officials
said.
   Labor Minister Chang Yung-chul and Social Affairs Minister Moon
Tai-joon are expected to take the blame for recent violent labor
strikes for higher pay, the officials said. Construction Minister
Park Seung may be removed because of widespread land speculation
caused by plans to build new cities, they said.
</TEXT>
