<FIRST>r i PM-Sweden-Palme 1stLd-Writethru   05-29 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sweden-Palme, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0511,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Indicted In Prime Minister's Slaying</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with seven grafs to include background on bungled investigation;
picks up 7th pvs: Pettersson has...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HELENE MURDOCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors today indicted a
42-year-old man on charges that he shot and killed Prime Minister
Olof Palme on a dark street in 1986 as the popular leader left a
movie with his wife.
   The 3,000-page indictment against Carl Gustav Christer
Pettersson also charged him with attempting to murder Palme's
widow, Lisbet, who was slightly wounded.
   ``I am convinced that this is enough to win a conviction,'' said
Stockholm Presecutor Jorgen Almbland. ``This is a step toward a
sentence.''
   Palme, a dynamic four-term prime minister, was gunned down Feb.
28, 1986, by a man who fled down a darkened lane and disappeared.
   The indictment ended a bumbling three-year investigation during
which investigators were branded incompetent by several official
inquiries. Three police chiefs and a justice minister resigned in
connection with the case.
   Pettersson, who has a previous manslaughter conviction on a
record sheet of more than 60 crimes, was routinely questioned
during the initial weeks of the investigation, but he was let go.
   The early stages of the investigation focused on the theory that
Palme was the victim of an international conspiracy. Stockholm
police chief Hans Holmer was fired after a 12-month effort as head
of the investigation when he refused to give up his discredited
theory that Kurdish terrorists assassinated Palme.
   Late last year, the investigation shifted after an anonymous tip
about discrepancies in Pettersson's alibi. He was arrested in
December.
   Pettersson has denied killing Palme. The trial was set to open
June 5.
   No motive was given. ``It's not up to us to prove that he had a
motive or what the motive was,'' said Anders Helin, the prosecutor
in charge of the case.
   The indictment listed 33 prosecution witnesses who claimed to
have seen Pettersson near the Grand Cinema or watched him follow
the Palmes after they left the movies and were walking home.
   A summary of the prosecution's case said Pettersson ``willfully
killed Prime Minister Olof Palme by shooting him in the back...''
   ``Pettersson, at the same time, attempted to kill Lisbet Palme
by firing again toward her,'' it said. ``Alternatively, he
endangered her life through gross negligence by firing the gun.''
   Mrs. Palme was listed as a witness, but the indictment gave no
indication of whether she would testify that she saw Pettersson
fire the gun.
   The evidence was largely circumstantial, and prosecutors
acknowledged they lacked the murder weapon and other forensic
evidence linking Pettersson to the shooting.
   ``It's a very strong case, but of course it would have been
better if we would have technical evidence,'' said Helin.
   Helin arrived at the courtroom carrying the indictment and the
evidence in a carton, which he presented to the court clerk.
   The prosecution is expected to present four witnesses who said
they saw Pettersson outside the theater at the time the movie began
and when it finished two hours later.
   Another two witnesses are expected to testify they saw
Pettersson follow the Palmes after the film. Eleven will testify
about Pettersson's possible motives, his opportunity to obtain a
weapon and his lack of a solid alibi.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
