<FILEID>AP-NR-05-29-89 0944EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Israel     05-29 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0536</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldier Apologizes For Using Pages of Koran as Toilet Paper</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli soldier apologized today for using
pages from the Koran, the Islamic holy book, as toilet paper while
troops occupied a school during a curfew in the West Bank, an army
spokesman said.
   In the occupied lands, three Palestinians were wounded, one
seriously, in clashes between soldiers and stone-throwing youths,
according to Arab reports.
   In Israel, armed force's chief of staff, Lt. Gen. Dan Shomron,
said that persistent attacks on Palestinians by Jewish settlers in
the territories is contributing to an escalation of violence in the
area.
   The desecration of the Koran in Deir Balout village was reported
by three newspapers and Israel radio after it was discovered over
the weekend by high school headmaster, Khalil Abdel Jawad. Eleven
pages of the Koran littered the bathroom floor and schoolyard, the
Haaretz and Jerusalem Post dailies said.
   Another entire volume of the Koran was found in a bathroom
cubicle, while drawings of an Israeli flag and cannon were
scribbled on a classroom blackboard, the newspapers said.
   Palestinian schools, closed by the Israeli military to contain
the 17-month-old uprising against Israeli rule, are frequently used
as temporary barracks during raids on villages.
   An army spokesman confirmed the school master ``found pages of
the holy Koran that had been used as toilet paper.''
   A soldier who confessed to the incident ``apologized, saying he
did not read Arabic and did not know that it was a Koran,'' the
spokesman said.
   Troops who occupied the school during the May 22-24 curfew were
told the signficance of what happened so it would not recur, the
spokesman said. No further disciplinary measures were planned, he
said.
   The curfew was imposed on the village while Israeli soldiers
conducted a search-and-arrest raid, Arab reports said.
   Shomron's warning to settlers came at the weekly Cabinet
session, which focused on spiraling clashes between the 70,000
Jewish settlers and the 1.7 million Palestinians in the
territories, Israeli newspapers said today.
   Referring to settler attacks on Palestinian homes and vehicles,
Shomron was quoted as saying: ``The army doesn't need to be spurred
on by the settlers who are taking independent action against
Arabs.''
   In response, a settlement leader, Rabbi Moshe Levinger, speaking
on Isreal radio, accused the government of failing to provide
adequate protection against stoning attacks by Palestinians.
   Levinger will stand trial next month for manslaughter in the
August 1988 shooting death of a Palestinian merchant.
   Eighteen of the 498 Palestinians who have been killed in the
Palestinian uprising are believed to have been slain by Israeli
civilians. Twenty-two Israelis also have died in the violence.
   The worst clash today occurred in Silwad in the West Bank when
troops opened fire on youths who tried to prevent the soldiers from
entering the village, Arab reports said. A 25-year-old man was
reported in serious condition at Ramallah hospital with a gunshot
wound in the head.
   In the Gaza Strip, two Palestinians, aged 8 and 13, were
reported hospitalized with gunshot wounds after throwing stones at
soldiers.
</TEXT>
