<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Cities     05-29 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Cities,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sister Cities Conference Opens in Soviet Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The inaugural conference of U.S.-Soviet sister
cities opened in Tashkent on Monday with messages from President
Bush and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev praising the program as
a bridge between the two nations.
   Officials, educators and community leaders from about 100 cities
in the United States and the Soviet Union gathered in the
Uzbekistan capital, 1,500 miles southeast of Moscow, to discuss the
linking of cities and exchange programs, the official Tass news
agency said. Tashkent is the sister city of Seattle.
   ``The rapid expansion of the sister cities program reflects the
desire for increased contacts between the American and Soviet
people,'' Bush said in a telegram to the conference, expected to
last three days.
   Tass transmitted the remarks of both Gorbachev and Bush.
   Bush said the twin cities program proved its effectiveness in
relief operations following the Armenian earthquake in December
that killed 25,000 people and left hundreds of thousands homeless.
   ``I had an opportunity to learn firsthand about sister city
activities when I met with Vice Mayor Babken Vardanyan of Yerevan,
Armenia, and Vice Mayor Alice Wolf of Cambridge, Mass., for a
briefing on the Yerevan-Cambridge program and its role in assisting
earthquake relief efforts in Armenia,'' Bush said.
   He said the program had transcended ceremonial exchanges and
emerged as a platform for practical partnerships.
   Gorbachev, in his message to the conference, said the sister
cities program was an effective form of diplomacy. ``It enhances
the human dimension of Soviet-American relations and enables
thousands of people, Soviet and American citizens, to get
acquainted, discuss questions of interest and work jointly,'' he
said.
   ``I would like to thank again American cities whose people
showed genuine human solidarity when the earthquake hit Armenia,''
Gorbachev said.
   He said the program did away with stereotypes inherited from the
Cold War and helped build confidence between the two nations.
</TEXT>
