<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Cyclone     05-29 0175</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Cyclone,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cyclone Kills Scores in Bangladesh</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cyclone that tore across Bangladesh
and eastern India killed at least 84 people and left more than half
a million homeless, officials and news reports said Monday.
   Tens of thousands of mud and straw huts were blown away during
the storm on Saturday that was accompanied by winds up to 85 mph,
they said.
   At least 49 people died in India and 35 in Bangladesh, they said.
   Relief Ministry officials said the storm also injured 600 people
in Bangladesh.
   The officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
death toll was likely to rise because at least 150 fishermen were
missing and feared dead in the Bay of Bengal off the southwestern
coast.
   An Indian news agency, Press Trust of India, said at least 33
people died after the cyclone struck the eastern Indian state of
West Bengal. At least 16 people died in neighboring Orissa state,
it said.
   The storm also left at least 500,000 people homeless in the two
states.
