<DOCNO> AP890529-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-29-89 1234EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Poll     05-29 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Poll,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deputies Doubt They Can Solve Economic Problems</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliamentarians regard raising their
constituents' standard of living as the government's most important
task, but they doubt that they can do much about it, according to a
poll released Monday.
   The Communist Party academy that conducted the poll said it
found roughly half the members of the new Congress of People's
Deputies hold relatively moderate views, whereas there appear to be
more reformers than conservatives in the body.
   The poll results, distributed at the congress, reported 74
percent of the members questioned said ``progess toward a higher
standard of living'' was the most important goal.
   In answer to another question, 55 percent said they thought
their sessions could have a positive, but not significant, effect
on living standards, and 27 percent said they could do nothing to
improve economic conditions.
   The poll of 1,347 of the 2,250 deputies was conducted Saturday
by the Communist Party Central Committee's Academy of Social
Sciences. That was the same day the congress broke into an angry
debate over the selection of members of the 542 members of the
Supreme Soviet standing legislature.
   An outnumbered group of reformers complained that regional
officials had stacked the lists of candidates with legislators who
would preserve the status quo.
   The pollsters said the balance of power in the session was held
by a moderate group of about 40 percent to 55 percent of the
deputies.
   Their report also identified a ``group with more radical
expectations and lesser satisfaction'' consisting of about 25
percent to 30 percent of those polled, and on the other side a
group with ``more cautious approaches, exhibiting a greater degree
of satisfaction'' consisting of about 15 percent to 20 percent of
the members.
   The deputies said they could have the greatest effect in making
Soviet society more open and democratic. Sixty percent responded
they could significantly improve openness and freedom of speech,
and another 29 percent said they were capable of making a less
noticeable improvement.
   The report said 74 percent did not regard the opening of Soviet
society as irreversible or considered the changes so far as only
half-measures.
   The proceedings of the body, ranging from long-winded discussion
of parliamentary procedure to angry debate and pointed
interrogation of the Kremlin leadership, have been televised live.
   The figures also indicated that 55 percent found their
expectations of the congress more or less fulfilled by its first
days, but an almost equal number _ 54 percent _ were dissatisfied
with the handling of procedural questions. Twenty-seven percent
were most upset about the behavior of other deputies, and 26
percent were most upset by a lack of organization.
   A poll of 1,832 citizens by the Soviet Academy of Sciences in
six cities on Friday indicated a vast majority of those polled were
following the Congress carefully in broadcasts from Moscow and
generally approved of what they saw. That poll was published Monday
by the government newspaper Izvestia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890529-0077 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-29-89 1247EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-SummitRdp 7thLd-Writethru a0533 05-29 1298</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Summit Rdp, 7th Ld-Writethru, a0533,1250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Proposes 20 Percent Cut in U.S. Combat Troops in Europe</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 5th graf pvs, Bush's plan, with NATO leaders
endorsing proposal; picks up 6th graf pvs, U.S. troop</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today proposed a 20
percent cut in U.S. combat troops in Europe and challenged Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev to order comparable troop
withdrawals to ``transform the military map'' by 1993.
   ``Here we go now, on the offense, with a proposal that will test
the Soviet Union,'' said Bush, clearly seeking to seize the
initiative in East-West relations at the opening of the two-day
NATO summit.
   Finessing a divisive quarrel among Western leaders over the
issue of modernizing short-range nuclear missiles, Bush countered
Gorbachev's recent disarmament proposals with a major plan to
achieve balance between the conventional forces of NATO and
East-bloc Warsaw Pact armies.
   Challenging Gorbachev at a televised news conference after he
outlined his proposals for 15 other NATO leaders, Bush asked: ``How
serious are you? Do you really want to reduce the imbalance ... or
do you just want rhetoric?''
   Bush's plan includes a ceiling of 275,000 troops each for the
American and Soviet sides in Europe, which would require a 20
percent reduction in U.S. troop strength and a withdrawal of
325,000 Soviet troops to achieve the same level.
   Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney said NATO leaders
unanimously endorsed the proposal, which is to be offered at
conventional forces talks with the Soviets.
   U.S. troop levels in Western Europe now range between 305,000
and 325,000, while some Western estimates put Soviet troop strength
in Central and Eastern Europe at more than 600,000.
   The 20 percent reduction applies to the 150,000 U.S. combat
troops stationed in NATO countries. Once an additional 150,000
support personnel are taken into account, Bush's cutback would
affect about 10 percent of the U.S. military force in Europe.
   After first briefing the Western allies privately, Bush sent
Gorbachev a letter on Sunday outlining the U.S. proposals.
   Today, Bush won an enthusiastic response from Western leaders
who had been pressing Washington to regain the offensive from
Gorbachev.
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher said Bush's proposals
had ``transformed the summit,'' and West German Chancellor Helmut
Kohl _ a key figure in the missile dispute _ hailed the president's
``great initiative for rapidly reducing conventional arms.''
   Bush thus succeeded in taking the summit spotlight away from
West Germany's demands for early East-West negotiations to reduce
and perhaps eliminate short-range nuclear missiles in Europe.
   Bush ruled out any such negotiations soon, at least until a
comprehensive conventional arms agreement is implemented, and said
he would never accept the idea of a nuclear-free Europe.
   The president said a NATO working group had been established to
seek a compromise on the missile dispute.
   In another major move, Bush said he was recommending that the
West drpop its nine-year automatic ban on transfers of computers
and other high technology to the Soviet Union. This economic
sanction was imposed after the Soviet intervention in Afghanistan
in December 1979.
   If the NATO allies give their expected approval, such transfers
would be considered on a case-by-case basis to determine if they
posed a threat to Western security.
   Facing criticism that he has moved too cautiously in responding
to Soviet arms proposals, Bush said, ``Here we go now on the
offense'' with the plan to reduce conventional forces in Europe.
   His plan also included NATO willingness for the first time to
negotiate limits on combat helicopters and aircraft throughout
Europe as part of a convention arms agreement.
   Bush also proposed locking in Soviet acceptance of proposed
Western ceilings on each side's arsenals of tanks and armored troop
carriers, and said a similar ceiling on artillery would be sought.
   Bush urged his NATO partners to endorse his plan and send it to
allied negotiators in conventional force talks with the Soviet-led
Warsaw Pact which began in Vienna, Austria, last March.
   He said an agreement could be reached in six months ``or maybe a
year'' if all went well and could be implemented by 1992 or 1993.
   The president said Secretary of States James A. Baker III was
available to meet with Gorbachev or Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze, ``the sooner the better.''
   ``If it were accepted, it would be a revolutionary conventional
arms control agreement,'' Bush said.
   ``If the Soviet Union accepts this fair offer, the results would
dramatically increase stabililty on the continent and transform the
military map of Europe,'' he said. ``We can and must begin now to
set out a new vision for Europe at the end of this century.''
   Early this month, Gorbachev offered to accept ceilings on Soviet
forces in all Warsaw Pact countries as well as a ceiling on overall
Soviet forces.
   Bush called his proposals ``a fair offer'' that ``signals a
willingness on our part to really put Mr. Gorbachev to the test.''
   Kohl congratulated Bush for ``this far-sighted step, with which
he has once more impressively affirmed the United States'
leadership.''
   Although Mrs. Thatcher was similarly complimentary, she warned
that ``the interim period will be a time of vulnerability and
risk'' that required maintaining a sufficiency of short-range
nuclear missiles on the continent.
   A small band of protesters prayed, beat drums and distributed
leaflets as Bush entered NATO headquarters this morning with
Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney.
   The two days of talks in the barracks-like alliance headquarters
opened with an address by NATO Secretary-General Manfred Woerner,
who warned against letting the missile dispute jeopardize NATO's
unity in dealing with the Soviets.
   ``Only if we remain united will we determine events,'' Woerner
said. ``Divided, even with all our successes and dynamism, we will
be the victims of events determined by others _ all of us, without
exception.''
   The NATO chief said Gorbachev's reforms were evidence that ``the
East is turning to the West'' and that ``communism has manifestly
failed.''
   But Woerner warned summit leaders against putting their trust in
Gorbachev's good intentions.
   For years, he said, the West will face ``a formidable and
unpredictable military power as our neighbor.'' And while ``we do
not need permanently to suspect his intentions ...'' he said, ``we
cannot build our security on the assumption of his permanent good
will.''
   Outside the main entrance to NATO headquarters, a dozen Japanese
Buddhist monks beat drums and prayed next to a sign in French which
read, ``NATO Bloc, 40 Years is Enough.''
   Other demonstrators handed out leaflets boasting of ``the
imminent separation of the USA from Europe'' because of the dispute
over short-range nuclear missiles and Gorbachev's arms reduction
offers.
   Bush, arriving Sunday evening from a two-day visit to Italy,
declared that ``NATO is at once ready to ensure the common defense
and to reduce arms and seek to diminish tensions with the East.''
   Although the summit had been billed as a celebration of NATO's
40th anniversary, the talks were clouded by discord largely between
the United States and Britain on one side, and West Germany on the
other.
   Responding to disarmament sentiment in West Germany, Bonn has
called for early East-West negotiations on short-range missiles,
most of which are based in West Germany and would be used against
forces on German soil.
   The United States says the weapons are needed to offset superior
conventional forces in the Soviet-led Warsaw Pact.
   West German Foreign Minister Hans-dietrich Genscher insisted
Sunday at a German political rally that ``disarmament cannot
exclude any kind of weapon.''
   A spokesman for Mrs. Thatcher said it was possible no deal on
the missile issue would be reached at the summit. ``We aren't in
the business of a bad agreement. We are in the business of
retaining flexible defense,'' said the official, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
