<FIRST>r i AM-BarbaraBush     05-29 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Barbara Bush,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Lady Comforts Handicapped Adult Overcome By Emotion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINA MACKENZIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First lady Barbara Bush, accompanied by
Belgium's Queen Fabiola, on Monday comforted a young woman who was
overcome with emotion during a presentation to the president's wife
at a special village for mentally handicapped adults.
   Mrs. Bush, in Brussels with her husband for the NATO summit,
toured the village while the president outlined dramatic new arms
control proposals to the Western leaders.
   The 20-year-old woman, identified only by her first name,
Beatrice, was overcome as she gave the president's wife a
puppet-like witch on a broomstick that she had made herself.
   Mrs. Bush took the present and then, realizing that the young
woman was crying, stepped over and patted her comfortingly on the
shoulder.
   The incident came at the end of the visit by Mrs. Bush and the
queen to the village 20 miles south of Brussels.
   The village, financed mainly with government funds, is home to
175 mentally handicapped adults. It was founded in 1963 by parents
wanting to provide a long-term home for their children once family
members are dead or can no longer care for them.
   ``It's an absolutely wonderful project,'' said Mrs. Bush, adding
that she felt ``honored to be here.''
   The converted brick farmhouse and outlying houses lie in the
shade of trees in quiet gardens filled with flowers. ``It's a very
peaceful place,'' said Mrs. Bush.
   Beatrice, still looking a bit shaken, said afterward that
meeting Mrs. Bush had made her ``very emotional.''
   At one point, the first lady asked Jean Wauters, the president
of the village, about the residency program and whether the
residents were separated from their families.
   The residents live in duplex homes in groups of 12 with a
married couple who look after them. But the residents do their own
housework, choose their menus and, as Mrs. Bush noted, decorate
their bedrooms to their taste.
   During the day, residents work in a shop counting supermarket
discount coupons _ the only such operation in Belgium _ or package
supermarket goods.
   For their 7{-hour working day, the residents are paid between
108 and 210 Belgian francs an hour ($2.50 to $5), which is the
going rate for Belgian manual laborers, said Catherine Mottet, a
psychologist at the village.
   Mrs. Bush was welcomed by two 20-year-old resident, Robert and
Judith, at the start of the morning tour. They gave the first lady
and the queen bouquets of red, white and blue flowers. Judith
needed a little encouragement from the educator who accompanied
them to part with her flowers.
   Mrs. Bush and Fabiola kissed the two.
   The first lady said that more such residences were needed in the
United States.
   Mrs. Bush regretted that she spoke no French. ``I just wish I
could say in French what I really feel.'' But she did manage
``merci beaucoup'' _ thank you very much.
   Mrs. Bush donated to the village a machine for ear, nose and
throat examinations.
</TEXT>
