<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Settlers Bjt   05-29 0759</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Settlers, Bjt,0782</SECOND>
<HEAD>Frustrated Jewish Settlers Launching Raids Against Arabs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARIEH O'SULLIVAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>and</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>HAITHAM HAMAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writers</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HEBRON, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many Jewish settlers in the
occupied lands believe the army is complacent about stonings and
firebomb attacks, and they are making their own response with raids
on Palestinian communities.
   They beat and shoot Palestinians, burn cars and smash the
windows of houses.
   In a rampage Monday, West Bank settlers attacked Kifl Harith
village near the Ariel settlement, setting crops, olive trees and a
house ablaze. Villagers threw stones and the settlers opened fire,
killing a 16-year-old girl and wounding two other Palestinians,
according to army and Arab reports.
   Her death brought to 18 the number of Arabs killed by Israeli
settlers in nearly 18 months of Palestinian rebellion. In all, 500
Palestinians have been slain, most by soldiers, and 22 Israelis
have died.
   Israeli commentators said the level of violence between the
70,000 settlers and 1.7 million Palestinians is unprecedented since
the uprising began in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Columnist Alex Fishman wrote in the independent newspaper
Hadashot: ``If it isn't stopped now, there will be mutual massacres
between Jews and Arabs.''
   The focus of tension in the West Bank is Hebron, a town of
80,000 Palestinians adjoined by Kiryat Arba, an outpost of 5,000
militant Jews who want the West Bank annexed to Israel.
   In a two-hour period on a recent weekday morning, a reporter saw
three motor patrols of settlers armed with Uzi submachine guns and
pistols drive through the center of town.
   Soldiers also make frequent patrols. Four young Palestinians
darted from a narrow alley and pelted two army jeeps with empty
bottles and rocks, but the troopers fired into the air and the
youths vanished.
   Maj. Gen. Amram Mitzna, army commander in the West Bank, was
quoted in the Jerusalem Post as telling a parliament committee ``an
explosive situation'' has developed ``because of settler attitudes
and actions.''
   He appealed to the lawmakers to help stop settlers from
assaulting soldiers who try to prevent vigilante raids.
   Settlers contend Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's government and
the army command are too lenient with the Palestinians.
   Noam Arnon, spokesman for the Gush Emunin settler movement, said
this week: ``The army doesn't do anything against the Arabs.''
   On the day Mitzna addressed the committee, settlers stopped
Palestinian motorists and beat three of them after a booby-trapped
Israeli flag with a swastika painted on it blew the hand off an
Israeli who picked it up.
   Arab reports said settlers also entered Burin village near
Nablus and beat two men in their homes.
   Last Thursdy night, after two firebombs narrowly missed a
settler outside Kiryat Arba, scores of settlers attacked an Arab
neighborhood of Hebron.
   Jawdat Jabari, 24, said about 100 Jews armed with rifles,
pistols and stones attacked his house, shouting ``Death to the
Arabs!'' He said stones shattered the porch windows and a burst of
gunfire hit the wall near the front door.
   His 21-year-old brother, Judeh, said the raiders knew the
Jabaris well because several members of the family worked at Kiryat
Arba.
   ``Most of those who stoned us used to come to this house and
drink coffee and tea without even knocking on the door,'' Judeh
said, and added angrily: ``There is no way that the Jews and the
Arabs can live together, ever. We will hate them wherever they go.''
   Fakri Attiyah Dana, a 50-year-old vegetable merchant, told of a
raid April 27 by about 50 settlers who burned 1,500 crates stored
on his roof, then shot holes in his water tank. He showed a
reporter 20 bullet holes in the walls.
   As he spoke, four teen-aged Israeli settlers stood on a nearby
hilltop with slingshots, launching stones at passing Arab
motorists. Soldiers arrived 15 minutes later and chased them away.
   Dana claimed five army jeeps accompanied the settlers April 27,
but an army spokesman denied that and other Palestinian claims of
soldiers joining settlers or doing nothing to stop them.
   He said some of the reports might be explained by settlers
wearing reserve army uniforms, a violation of regulations.
   Arnon said the raids were a warning to militant young
Palestinians ``to tell them: `Boys, take it easy. We can also do
something.''
   ``I don't hate anyone,'' said the Gush Emunin spokesman, who
directs the Kiryat Arba religious studies center. ``I want to live
with them in peace, but whosoever attacks me and wants to kill me,
I'll kill them. It is written in the Bible.''
</TEXT>
