<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-Race     05-29 0704</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Race,0727</SECOND>
<HEAD>Race Between Rivals Reveals Strains in Solidarity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A parliament race between a veteran
dissident and a prominent lawyer who once defended him has turned
into a struggle for the soul of the Solidarity-led opposition
movement.
   Jacek Kuron, a founder of the Polish opposition movement, has
been endorsed by Solidarity leader Lech Walesa in Sunday's
elections, the first competitive balloting in Poland under
communist rule.
   But Kuron is being challenged in his northern Warsaw district of
Zoliborz by lawyer Wladyslaw Sila-Nowicki, who defended Kuron
during the political trials in the 1970s.
   Kuron is among the best-known of Solidarity's intellectual
advisers, some of whom began as communists in the 1950s and 1960s
but broke with the party long ago. Those advisers have provided the
movement with theoretical ammunition in its struggle to wrest
freedoms from the government.
   Sila-Nowicki's roots are in the pre-World War II Christian
Democrats, a party that had strong ties to the Roman Catholic
Church and which is now reorganizing with the tacit approval from
some bishops and priests.
   As part of accords reached with communist authorities April 5,
the opposition agreed to support partially free elections to the
Sejm and a newly created Senate in return for legalizing Solidarity
after a seven-year ban.
   The opposition is allotted only 161 seats in the 460-seat Sejm,
with the rest reserved for the communists. The 100 seats in the
newly created Senate are open to all groups, making it the first
democratically elected legislative body in the East bloc.
   With his 30-year record of opposition activity that includes
eight years in prison, Kuron was a natural choice for Solidarity to
endorse for the Sejm.
   A former communist who was sent to prison for an open letter
urging the party to reform, he helped found the Workers Defense
Committee after authorities brutally suppressed strikes in 1976.
   Sila-Nowicki, 75, also has a long record serving the opposition.
   A soldier in the underground that which resisted Nazi and later
Soviet occupation, Sila-Nowicki notes he was condemned to death
four times and imprisoned from shortly after the end of World War
II until 1956.
   In the 1970s, he was one of the few lawyers willing to defend
activists who were continually being arrested.
   Sila-Nowicki also stresses his links to Solidarity in campaign
literature. On some posters his name has been painted to resemble
the familiar red-and-white Solidarity logo.
   He notes that he served as an adviser in Gdansk in 1980, when
Walesa signed the agreements that legalized the Soviet bloc's first
free trade union. It was outlawed 18 months later after the martial
law crackdown.
   Solidarity candidates posed for photos with Walesa as a mark of
authenticity. Sila-Nowicki responded with photos showing him with
Polish-born Pope John Paul II.
   But his campaign literature fails to mention that in 1986 he was
the only well-known independent figure who joined an advisory
council set up by Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski as proof
that national reconciliation was proceeding. Others refused, saying
Solidarity first should be legalized.
   Voters, unused to being able to choose anyone but officially
approved candidates, are confused.
   ``Is he on Lech's list?'' one woman asked a Sila-Nowicki worker
at a table outside the St. Stanislaw Kostka Church, a Solidarity
stronghold. When she was told no, she said: ``Then he's not
Solidarity.''
   Sila-Nowicki is not from Zoliborz. Candidates can run where they
like, and Sila-Nowicki said he came to Zoliborz specifically to
challenge Kuron.
   ``We are presenting different visions of today's Solidarity,''
Sila-Nowicki told his first election meeting May 14.
   Sila-Nowicki accused Solidarity of not backing enough Christian
Democratic candidates and of choosing candidates without consulting
the rank and file.
   Seven Christian Democratic candidates are running nationwide,
but only one is endorsed by Solidarity. They support free markets
and the church's social teachings, such as opposition to abortion.
   ``There is a leftist direction in Solidarity. We would like to
see a Christian path,'' said Maciej Mazuriewicz, a 24-year-old
student supporter of Sila-Nowicki.
   When the two men debated on May 20, the 700 seats of the Wisla
theater were filled and hundreds more listened outside.
Sila-Nowicki received polite applause, but the crowd roared when
Kuron emerged.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
