<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Vietnam-Storm     05-29 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Vietnam-Storm,0187</SECOND>
<HEAD>Death Toll in Vietnam Storm Rises to 78</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The death toll from tropical storm
Cecil's destructive charge through central Vietnam last week has
risen to 78, and 364 other people are reported missing, the Vietnam
News Agency said Monday.
   The agency, monitored in Bangkok, said 50 other people were
injured when the storm hit the coastal province of Quang Nam-Danang
Thursday and Friday. About 150,000 people were made homeless, it
said.
   The agency said the storm caused about $23 million in damage.
   It destroyed or damaged 23,500 houses, 150 schools and 3,000
boats, and rains submerged 49,400 acres of rice that was nearing
harvest, it said.
   The province's communications system was paralyzed, the report
said.
   President Vo Chi Cong sent a message of sympathy to the people
of the province, it said.
   Such storms annually cause major loss of life and damage in
Vietnam, which struggles to feed its fast-growing population.
   Cecil also dumped heavy rain in Thailand and Laos before
crossing late Saturday into Burma, where it weakened, Thailand's
Meteorological Department said.
</TEXT>
