<FILEID>AP-NR-05-29-89 1324EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-LewisHometown     05-29 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lewis Hometown,0642</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sinclair Lewis' Hometown Will Ignore Author's Criticism, Use His
Name</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAUK CENTRE, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of this town whose
``incredible dullness'' bored Sinclair Lewis into writing ``Main
Street'' say it's time to set aside bad feelings toward the author
and capitalize on his fame.
   But the plans are met with skepticism by some who believe Lewis
was right when his ``Main Street'' lambasted the fictional Gopher
Prairie, Minn., a thinly disguised version of the central Minnesota
town where Lewis was born in 1885.
   ``So they want to redevelop things historically. That's what
I've always tried to do. But I never could get this town to wake up
and realize Sinclair Lewis gives them the greatest cottage industry
in the world,'' said Al Tingley, who is selling the Palmer House
Hotel he has owned for 15 years.
   ``I'd love to see Sauk Centre be all it can be,'' he said.
``That's exactly what Sinclair Lewis was trying to tell them:
Realize what you have and try to do more.
   ``But I don't think it'll work. This town never changes.''
   The feeling that the town of 3,700, about 95 miles northwest of
Minneapolis, has not taken advantage of Lewis' legacy moved
business owners and local officials to ask for help from Charlie
Nelson, an architect from the Minnesota Historical Society.
   Nelson looked at the hodgepodge of signs, aluminum siding and
bland paint and described the town as ``a mess of plastic and
kitsch.''
   ``They've got some pretty well-preserved buildings behind all
that tin and plastic,'' Nelson said. ``But downtown is kind of a
void. It's too easy to get out of there without knowing you've ever
been there.''
   Nelson told his hosts they should use paint, awnings and elbow
grease to bring their downtown buildings back to something
resembling their original appearance and make the place more
inviting and evocative.
   Mayor Bob Polipnick said the city should ``use Lewis as much as
we can.''
   ``I don't really care if what he said was positive or negative,
as long as people remember Sauk Centre,'' he said.
   Often pitiless about his town, Lewis railed against ``the
incredible dullness of it,'' ``its vacuousness and bad manners and
spiteful gossip.'' In the 1920 novel ``Main Street,'' when heroine
Carol Kennicott arrived in the fictional Gopher Prairie she found
``no dignity in it nor any hope of greatness. It was not a place to
live in, not possibly, not conceivably.''
   Among Lewis' other novels are ``Babbitt,'' ``Elmer Gantry,''
``Arrowsmith'' and ``It Can't Happen Here.'' In 1930, he became the
first American to win the Nobel Prize in literature. He died in
1951.
   Dave Simpkins, who publishes the newspaper where Lewis once
worked, said the revitalization push doesn't mean someone is
``trying to come in and tell people what they ought to do _ that's
what Carol Kennicott tried.''
   If enough business owners go along, he said, ``we can give the
tourists something unique so someone from Omaha will want to
come.'' The town is conveniently situated along Interstate 94,
between Minneapolis and Fargo, N.D.
   Carol Frumkin hopes to be the person to turn the hotel _ and
maybe the town _ around. Frumkin, returning to Sauk Centre 23 years
after she left, has the capital needed to make the Palmer House a
luxury hotel.
   She and her husband are moving to a farm outside town this
summer, bringing their wood products import business from
California. She pledges to turn the Palmer House into ``a small,
elegant, comfortable hotel, with a fine restaurant. We'll refurbish
everything.''
   But ``if you just have the Palmer House, it's nothing,'' Frumkin
said. ``People don't want to come here and just sit in the hotel.
The rest of downtown has to be interesting, too.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
