<FIRST>r i AM-Italy-Bombs     05-29 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Bombs,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bombs Cause Damage at Four Montedison, Shell Italia Plants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bombs exploded early Monday at buildings
owned by the Italian chemical group Montedison and at the
headquarters of Shell Italia, causing damage but no injuries.
   Other early morning blasts at Selm near Milan and at Cengio near
Savona damaged pylons for high tension electric lines that served
Montedison plants, officials said.
   No group claimed responsibility for the blasts, which caused
damage that Montedison officials estimated at $1 million.
   Shell spokesman Gian Luca Chiavari said the company received no
warning before the blast that shattered a window and caused minor
damage to a conference room.
   In 1987, Shell established a joint venture with Montedison, the
other bombing target, for gasoline distribution to retail stations,
he said.
   The first bomb exploded at 2:30 a.m. near the side entrance of
Montedison's headquarters in Milan, breaking windows and damaging a
wall and cars that were parked nearby.
   About the same time, a bomb caused a fire that destroyed two
transformers at a Montedison plant near Rho in Milan Province.
   At 5 a.m., bombs damaged pylons for high tension electric lines
carrying power to plants at Selm and Cengio.
   Chiavari said the bomb exploded about 2:30 a.m. outside the
headquarters of Shell Italia.
</TEXT>
