<FIRST>r a AM-HighwayKillings     05-29 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Highway Killings,0675</SECOND>
<HEAD>Serial Killer Stalks Women on Parallel Paths</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW BEDFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sandra Botelho and Christina Monteiro
lived parallel lives, growing up in this city's Brickenwood housing
project surrounded by toddlers, lines of fresh laundry and hard
drugs.
   Their side-by-side lives may also have taken them into the path
of a serial killer. Botelho's body was one of nine found along
several highways near this historic port city since last July.
Monteiro is one of two women missing and believed dead.
   There have been no arrests despite an extensive police
investigation.
   Like most of the killer or killers' targets, Botelho and
Monteiro sold their bodies at $20 a shot and bought heroin with the
cash.
   Sitting around a dinner table, Monteiro's brothers and sisters
threw out easy memories of their sister, who loved swimming, family
picnics and dancing to rhythm and blues.
   Shirley Monteiro took down from shelves framed photographs of
first communions and her daughter, who would now be 21, grinning
wide at her baby shower three years ago.
   But Monteiro, like 25-year-old Botelho, got caught in a web of
drugs.
   ``They were good friends,'' said Deborah Botelho, Sandra's
sister. ``They shared clothes together, went dancing together and
shot up together.''
   Botelho had spent 10 years with a man relatives say was abusive.
But in the last months of her life she still struggled to get a
high school equivalency diploma, and entertained thoughts of
becoming a secretary.
   Her sister said she even thought about becoming ``a cop _ if you
can believe that.''
   She kept ending up back on the streets.
   Still, friends and family say, Sandra Botelho's two sons, age 5
and 7, always had clean clothes and food.
   ``It's hard to stay up all night doing drugs and be up cooking
eggs for the kids in the morning, but she did it,'' said Deborah
Botelho.
   Commitment to family runs deep at the Brickenwood project, one
of several developments on the city's north end, which is home to
mostly Roman Catholic families, predominantly of Portuguese and
Cape Verdian descent.
   Shirley Monteiro, who now is caring for her 3-year-old grandson,
said her daughter moved out when she was about 17.
   ``That's when I started seeing the tracks on her arms,'' she
said.
   Mrs. Monteiro decided to take action when she learned her
daughter had moved to prostitution.
   ``I was very bold,'' she said. ``I barged right in on her
apartment one time when a few guys were there and kicked the bed,
rolled over the mattress and started throwing pillows. But it still
didn't help.''
   Neither did Deborah Botelho's efforts save her sister.
   ``Sandy was calling around and looking into rehab centers,'' she
said. ``I said I'd take her kids if she followed through on it, but
I wasn't going to be a sucker at home while she was out on the
streets doing drugs.''
   The last time Deborah Botelho, 23, saw her sister was at a
cookout last August.
   ``Sandy and I always had a ball. And that night was no
different,'' Botelho said. ``She talked more about drugs and where
she was getting them, but she was still the same old Sandy.''
   The following week, Sandy was gone. Her body was found in April.
   That same August night while the Botelhos were barbecuing, the
Monteiros gathered next door on their front porch, eating ice
cream, talking, wondering where Christina might be. She had been
missing since June.
   The month before Christina disappeared, she wrote a Mother's Day
poem in neat, slanting script on paper now frayed from rereading.
She wrote of her pain, fear and desire to ``straighten out'' and
make her mother proud.
   Some relatives hold out hope she simply moved away to get a
fresh start. Investigators say it is more likely that her fate was
similar to that of her friend Sandy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
