<DOCNO> AP890529-0090 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-29-89 1335EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PilotMemorial     05-29 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pilot Memorial,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mother Of Vietnam Pilot Waited 22{ Years For Grim But Reassuring
News</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Memorial Day Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LENOX, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jeanette Coakley waited 22{ years for the
grim news she calls her best Mother's Day gift ever: the
reassurance that her son died instantly when his jet crashed in
Vietnam.
   ``Oh, what a relief,'' said Mrs. Coakley, 84. ``I just felt I
might die and never know. Now I have that.''
   The long-missing remains of Navy Lt. Cmdr. William F. Coakley
were to be buried Tuesday with full military honors in a cemetery
near the house his father and grandfather built a half-century ago.
The funeral should also bury the fears of the family that for two
decades did not know the pilot's fate.
   Mrs. Coakley, wearing the pin that designates her a Gold Star
mother, said she learned of her oldest son's fate just before
Mother's Day. The remains were among 17 sets that the Defense
Department has positively identified since the Vietnamese
government turned them over five months ago.
   ``I just had such tremendous faith that God would answer my
prayers,'' she said last week seated in her living room below a
photograph of her son with former President Lyndon Johnson and his
wife, Lady Bird.
   Coakley was 33 and on his 44th combat mission when his Skyhawk
jet went down on Sept. 13, 1966, over the North Vietnam province of
Thanh Hoa. His death came only six weeks after his youngest brother
was hit and killed by a drunken driver in their hometown.
   Handsome and smart, Coakley graduated No. 1 in his class at a
private Jesuit high school in 1953, reaped honors at Holy Cross
College and was sent by the Navy to earn a master's degree in
political affairs at Harvard University, according to his younger
brother, Robert, now 51.
   ``He had the world the way you'd want it,'' said Robert, who
heads the guidance department at the local high school.
   As a Navy social aide, Coakley escorted actresses and socialites
at White House parties from 1963 to 1965, but gave up his
prestigious job to go to Vietnam.
   ``He felt it wasn't right that he was in the White House and his
friends were out there fighting,'' his mother said.
   Coakley returned to Vietnam after his brother's death although
he could have stayed home on compassionate leave. He would have
been back in Lenox in another three months and had decided to go to
medical school.
   ``He knew what he was facing when he went back to Vietnam
because they were facing terrible, terrible odds up there,'' saids
Robert Coakley. ``The Navy was very shorthanded with pilots.''
   He said the Navy never learned what caused the jet to go down.
Another pilot noticed it was off course and radioed to Coakley to
straighten out. ``The last thing he said was, `I'm trying,''' his
brother said.
   He called the next two decades a nightmare. ``The terrible
uncertainty, the lingering despair of not knowing, are feelings I
cannot accurately describe,'' he said in a speech five years ago.
   The uncertainty vanished with a forensic report from Navy
officials last week. ``It's amazing what they can tell,'' said
Coakley, who said he did not want to go into details to spare his
mother's feelings.
   ``The most comforting things to us were that No. 1, there's no
question it was Bill, and secondly, he died instantly.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890529-0091 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-29-89 1341EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-HouseLeadership 1stLd-Writethru a0562 05-29 1215</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-House Leadership, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0562,1,000</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDS: Subs 9th graf, ``When it xxx to restore dropped wort ``resulted''</HEAD>
<HEAD>Wright Went it Alone as Speaker _ From Beginning to End</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jim Wright's daring call for a tax increase
the day he became speaker of the House foretold a single-minded
style of confronting issues that marked both the doing and the
undoing of his 2{-year command.
   The rent in the House Democratic leadership that began with a
yearlong ethics investigation of Wright has unraveled into the
ranks with the weekend resignation of Rep. Tony Coelho _ No. 3 in
the pecking order _ and the jockeying for party power and position
that will follow the elevation of Majority Leader Tom Foley to
speaker.
   Wright, who is expected to resign this week, helped make the
100th Congress one of the most productive in years, with the
passage of major legislation on trade, welfare reform, fighting
drugs, a bipartisan budget agreement, and dozens of other important
items.
   But in the doing of that, Wright generated searing, personal
enmity among his Republican opponents without picking up a
counterbalancing loyalty from his Democratic colleagues.
   The combination left the Texas Democrat _ a veteran of 34 years
in the House _ too thinly protected when the attack came on his
personal financial ethics.
   Democrat Rep. Byron Dorgan of North Dakota summed up the Wright
legacy in two sentences: ``The legislative record in his short term
as speaker is an exceptional record. But the price for doing that
was extraordinarily high.''
   Fellow Democrat Rep. Charles Schumer of New York elaborated:
``Jim Wright was the quintessential go-it-alone guy. And that
accounted for his success and that accounted for his failures. When
he made up his mind to do something, he got it done ... but the
House isn't structured for that kind of thing.''
   Wright never won the tax increase that he contended _ as many
members still do privately _ was the only way the federal deficit
will be reduced substantially. His willingness to take hits to win
battles met with some notable success.
   When it became clear that the Reagan administration could no
longer muster support for its policy of arming the Nicaraguan
Contra rebels, Wright seized the initiative. He led negotiations
himself that resulted in new, non-lethal, ``humanitarian'' aid
packages for the rebels coupled with support of regional efforts to
work out a peace settlement.
   While the trail Wright blazed has essentially become U.S.
policy, he suffered intense criticism for trampling on prerogatives
usually reserved by the president.
   Maybe there simply was too much success for Wright's own good,
suggested Rep. David Bonior, D-Mich., a member of the speaker's
leadership team and a potential successor to Coelho.
   ``I think the leadership on our side was so successful that we
really posed a tremendous threat to the Republicans, and I think
because of that they decided that they needed to weaken the
leadership and they went after the speaker,'' he said.
   Dorgan said Wright would not tolerate the legislative foot
dragging that was the hallmark of Congress for years. ``That means
you step on some toes, and maybe run over some egos,'' said Dorgan.
``He didn't make a lot of friends.''
   Some of those toes and egos belonged to Democrats, who mostly
kept their gripes within the Democratic family _ but who were not
exactly eager to rush to Wright's public defense.
   Embittered Republicans, on the other hand, complained _ loudly _
that Wright's successes were won with strong-armed parliamentary
tactics that dictated the results and demeaned the institution of
the House.
   The defining confrontation came early in Wright's speakership.
   With budget talks with the Reagan White House just underway in
October, 1987, Wright insisted on going ahead with a Democratic
grab-bag bill of budget and tax items. Republicans rounded up the
votes to block it, and thought they had a rare victory.
   But an impatient Wright didn't let them savor their success. He
adjourned the House, declared a new legislative day _ a
parliamentary maneuver to leap to a new calendar day _ and muscled
the bill to passage by forcing a Texas colleague to change his vote.
   ``The speaker had a luncheon with the Republicans, and we tried
to patch things up,'' Bonior recalled.
   But Wright was the not the back-slapping, chummy guy who could
smooth over legislative brawls with his personality.
   ``It's clear that he doesn't have the same warm, effusive
personality that Tip (former speaker Thomas P. O'Neill) did. Jim
was a little more aloof than that, and a little more alone than
that,'' Dorgan said.
   Rep. Dick Cheney, a GOP leader who is now secretary of defense,
praised Wright at a dinner a few days before that pivotal budget
vote. Afterward, Cheney rarely had a kind word for the speaker and
helped file the ethics complaint that lined up the nails for
Wright's political coffin.
   Despite his bad relations with the Republicans, Wright was able
to push through all 13 of Congress' annual spending bills last year
_ the first time that had been accomplished in many years.
   But the 101st Congress began in January on a bad note for Wright.
   Already mired in controversy because of questions raised about
his ethics, Wright lost points with members of both parties with
his handling _ many of his colleagues termed it mishandling _ of
President Bush's recommendation that Congress receive a 50 percent
pay increase.
   Although he personally opposed such a big salary boost, Wright
tried to find a way to get it through for his colleagues.
Eventually, he backed down to supporting a 30 percent increase, and
the whole thing finally collapsed. Congress not only did not get
the pay raise, but took a bruising from the public.
   In typical style, Wright acted almost alone, absorbing most of
the criticism. Republican campaign officials helped fan the flames
of public outrage at Wright even though it was Bush's pay proposal.
   Republicans were angered by the Democratic Senate's rejection of
John Tower, Bush's first choice for defense secretary. And with the
legislative pace slowed in part because of a slow-moving new
administration, the spotlight locked on Wright's ethics.
   In a scenario that had all the earmarks of Wright's final days
as speaker, he tried last week to find a graceful exit. He
dispatched lawyers to see if the House ethics committee might
consider dropping some charges against him in return for his
stepping down.
   But the ethics committee is the one committee in the House where
Republicans have an equal vote with the Democrats, and they
publicly decried any ``deal-making.''
   The embittered Republicans wouldn't help their nemesis leave.
Democrats didn't rally to his defense, instead talking about an
orderly transition.
   And the speaker again was left to act on his own.
   If there was doubt he would step down, it was lessened by
Coelho's surprise resignation _ a move the California Democrat said
in part was intended to spare the party further turmoil stemming
from an almost certain protracted examination of his own ethics in
connection with his involvement in a junk bond purchase.
   Without saying so directly, Coelho was saying indirectly that if
he would step aside for the good of the party, so could anyone else.
</TEXT>
