<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan-Relief     05-29 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan-Relief,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Killed in Attack on U.N. Relief Convoy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHEGE MBITIRU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen attacked a United Nations convoy
carrying emergency food from Uganda to war-torn southern Sudan,
killing three people and seriously injuring one, a U.N official
said Monday.
   The nationality of the dead and injured were not known, but they
were not U.N. employees, said Diane Weathers, a spokeswoman for the
U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization in Nairobi. The time of the
attack was not known.
   The incident, the third of its kind, prompted U.N. officials to
postpone emergency food deliveries by road, but airlifts will
continue from Entebbe, Uganda, to Juba in southern Sudan, Ms.
Weathers said.
   The 20-truck convoy, carrying 270 tons of corn, was attacked
shortly after crossing the border from northwestern Uganda. The
convoy reported the attack Monday upon reaching its destination in
Yei, in Sudan's southeastern Equatoria province, Ms. Weathers said.
   One truck was destroyed by a land mine but it wasn't clear
whether the explosion and the attack occurred simultaneously, she
said.
   Further details of the attack by unidentified gunmen were not
immediately available.
   On Sunday, the first train carrying emergency supplies reached
its destination in southern Sudan town of Aweil, according to
Sudan's Transport Minister Fadlallah Burma Nasser. The train was
delayed for four days by armed bandits and broken rails, government
and relief officials said.
   The $130 million U.N.-sponsored relief operation began April 1
to stockpile 115,500 tons of food in southern Sudan before the
annual heavy rains turn roads and airstrips into mud. That would be
enough food to save 100,000 Sudanese from starving.
   Last year, as many as 500,000 Sudanese died in a famine provoked
in part by the 6-year-old civil war.
   The food is being ferried from neighboring Uganda, Kenya and
northern Sudan to be distributed equally in areas held by the
government and the Sudan People's Liberation Army.
   In 1983, the rebel army began fighting the Moslem government in
Khartoum. The rebels demand greater autonomy for the mainly
Christian and animist south.
   The rebels are observing a month's unilateral cease-fire to
permit emergency food and other supplies to reach southern Sudan.
   Even so, the U.N.-sponsored program has faced difficulties such
as the attacks by unidentified gunmen and a railroad strike. In
addition, Ethiopia has not permitted the relief program to truck
food on roads along that country's western border with Sudan.
   On May 21, 100 unidentified gunmen attacked the 48-car train
carrying 1,500 tons of food, and robbed three Western relief
officials of their personal belongings.
   In April, unidentified gunmen ambushed the first 47-truck convoy
from Kapoeta in southern Sudan, killing seven people.
</TEXT>
