<FIRST>u i AM-Summit-Reaction     05-29 0744</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Summit-Reaction,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Allies Hail Bush Proposals</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West European leaders on Monday hailed
U.S. proposals for cuts in Soviet and American troops and weapons
in Europe, temporarily shelving their quarrels over short-range
nuclear missiles.
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher declared that President
Bush had ``transformed the summit'' of the leaders of the 16-nation
North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
   She cautioned, though, that an era of risk and vulnerability lay
ahead for the West if the cutbacks in conventional, or non-nuclear,
forces were carried out.
   West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, Mrs. Thatcher's main
European antagonist in the nuclear dispute, applauded the United
States for ``a great initiative.''
   ``President Bush has today paved the way for further success of
our alliance,'' said Kohl. ``I congratulate him on this far-sighted
step with which he has once more impressively affirmed the United
States' leadership.''
   In Moscow, the Soviet news agency Tass reported the Bush plan,
adding that ``local observers note that the new proposals were made
by Washington after the Bush administration came under serious
criticism from the public for the lack of any disarmament
initiatives at a time when the Soviet Union has launched a `peace
offensive.'''
   At the summit's opening session, Bush proposed a joint reduction
in U.S. and Soviet troops stationed in Europe to 275,000 for each
side by 1993. He also urged sharp slashes in conventional weapons,
including tanks, and their destruction.
   He called on the allies to indicate their willingness to
negotiate limits on combat aircraft and helicopters in Europe to 15
percent below current NATO levels. All the removed equipment would
be destroyed.
   U.S. officials were delighted with the allies' reaction.
   A senior administration official, briefing reporters on
condition of anonymity, said the atmosphere as Bush unveiled his
initiative in a closed session of the Western alliance leaders was
``enthusiastic _ even warmer than anything we had reason to
expect.''
   Dutch, Spanish and Italian officials welcomed the move.
   Hubert Vedrine, a spokesman for French President Francois
Mitterrand, said France supports the Bush proposals but expressed
reservations about including aircraft in the conventional arms
bargaining.
   He said France's air forces cannot be included in the
negotiations because they contribute to the nation's independent
nuclear strategy. France is not a member of NATO's military
structure.
   The United States wants the NATO leaders to endorse Bush's plan
so that it can be put on the negotiating table at recently opened
talks in Vienna with the Warsaw Pact on reducing conventional
forces in Europe.
   The move at the start of a two-day summit took the spotlight off
what had promised to be a difficult meeting of the 16 allies,
marking NATO's 40th anniversary.
   The United States and Britain are leading the opposition to West
German demands for negotiations to reduce short-range nuclear
missiles.
   However, a cutback in conventional armaments _ where the Soviets
now have huge superiority _ would fulfill a U.S. condition for
entering short-range negotiations.
   Mrs. Thatcher, her spokesman reported, told the summit in closed
session that Bush's initiative ``went to the heart of the
superiority of the Soviet Union in conventional weapons.''
   But she said the Bush proposals, if accepted by Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev, ``would take a very considerable time to
achieve.''
   The British spokesman, who demanded anonymity, said Mrs.
Thatcher added that the ``interim period would therefore be a time
of vulnerability and risk'' making it essential for NATO to have
``a sufficiency of short-range nuclear forces.''
   Dutch Foreign Minister Hans van den Broek said Bush had given
``the Soviets an opportunity to show they are able and ready to
reduce their forces.''
   Van den Broek and several other European officials warned of
immediate difficulties for negotiators in agreeing on reductions in
helicopters and combat aircraft because of differing methods of
counting warplanes by the superpowers.
   Spanish Foreign Minister Franciso Fernandez Ordonez said Bush
had given a new impetus to the conventional arms talks.
   ``This proposal would reduce the possibility of a surprise
attack by the Warsaw Pact,'' he said, adding it enhanced the
chances of the NATO allies ``reaching a good agreement'' among
themselves in Brussels.
   Bush also pleased some regular critics. John Isaacs, spokesman
for a Washington-based anti-nuclear group, Council for a Livable
World, said arms control took ``two to tango.''
   ``We've had for the last couple of years Gorbachev quite willing
to tango ... he may have a partner in President Bush and NATO.''
</TEXT>
