<FIRST>u i AM-China-US 1stLd-Writethru a0549 05-29 0710</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-US, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0549,0726</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Ideals Influence Chinese Students</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to ADD that statue is made of styrofoam and
plaster of Paris, will be unveiled Tuesday. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, ``The
Goddess ...''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The towering ``Goddess of Democracy'' displayed
in Tiananmen Square by freedom-seeking Chinese students is sister
to the Statue of Liberty and dramatically highlights the influence
U.S. ideals have had on the protesters.
   ``At first we wanted to make it exactly like the Statue of
Liberty,'' said Ke Feng, a Beijing University student involved in
construction of the 33-foot styrofoam and plaster of Paris
monument. ``China needs this type of symbol.''
   The statue was being assembled at Tiananmen for unveiling
Tuesday.
   The Goddess of Democracy, feverishly built by Central Fine Arts
Academy student sculptors, differs slightly in design from the
152-foot copper statue in New York Harbor. Both depict a woman in
classical robes holding high a torch of freedom, although the
Chinese version does not hold a tablet.
   It is not the first time that U.S. influence on the protests for
democratic change has surfaced. Replicas of the Statue of Liberty
have been carried by marchers in Shanghai several times and have
appeared on campus posters in Beijing.
   ``America represents democracy and freedom,'' said Wang Yue, a
23-year-old senior at the Beijing Science and Technology
University, one of the students who gathered Monday night in
Tiananmen Square. ``I think most of the students received the idea
of democracy and freedom from America and other Western countries.''
   Information about the United States has become widely available
since China opened to the outside world a decade ago, and students
say they study U.S. history at school.
   More than 60,000 Chinese have gone to the United States to study
since 1978, and some of those who have come back participated in
the pro-democracy protests of the past six weeks.
   An English-language poster in Beijing recalled Patrick Henry's
immortal line, ``Give me liberty or give me death.'' Others have
quoted Nathan Hale and the Declaration of Independence.
   ``Of the people, by the people, for the people. This should be a
universal principle,'' a Petroleum University senior at Tiananmen
Square said Monday, recalling Abraham Lincoln's prescription for
good government in the Gettysburg Address.
   The student demonstrators, while not calling for the end of
Communist Party rule, clearly support U.S. political ideals such as
freedom of the press and the rule of law.
   ``We want our government to be more like America's,'' said one
student visiting Beijing from the northeastern industrial city of
Shenyang.
   Pro-democracy protesters are eager that their movement be viewed
positively in the United States and incessantly ask reporters about
the reaction of the Bush administration and Americans to the
demonstrations.
   The Chinese people have turned to the United States for
inspiration before when seeking political change.
   John Dewey, an American philosopher known for his pragmatism,
profoundly influenced some leaders of the May Fourth Movement of
1919, when students protested to demand democracy and science.
   Even communist revolutionary Mao Tse-tung is said to have been
impressed by George Washington and the American Revolution.
   The 1989 democracy protesters, however, view neither the United
States nor the Western world as the sole source of inspiration.
   Chinese students have followed with interest Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of ``glasnost,'' or openness, that
has eased press restrictions and allowed public political debate.
   The communist neighbors share recent histories of autocratic
government, and Gorbachev's political reforms are viewed by some
Chinese students as models for change in their own country.
   When the Soviet leader visited China from May 15-18, during the
height of the protests, several students carried welcoming signs in
Chinese and Russian. ``Welcome to a Real Reformer, Gorbachev,'' one
read. ``Democracy _ Our Common Ideal,'' said another.
   But when a group of students was asked Monday whether they
considered the United States or the Soviet Union a better model for
political change, they answered with a chorus, ``You can't put the
question like that.''
   They said neither system was suitable as a comprehensive model
for a new political system in China, which will have to travel its
own road to democracy.
</TEXT>
