<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     05-29 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Says Army Repels Offensive at Jalalabad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Assocation Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government reported a new
offensive around Jalalabad, which Moslem guerrillas have had under
siege since early March, but said Monday its soldiers repulsed the
insurgents with artillery fire.
   Mohammad Nabi Amani, spokesman for the Foreign Ministry, said at
least 139 guerrillas had been killed and 70 wounded since the
attack began Sunday. He did not give government casualties.
   Guerrillas based in neighboring Pakistan said the they began a
new attack Saturday on government posts around Jalalabad, 75 miles
east of Kabul. They claimed to have captured several posts and
killed or wounded 70 soldiers.
   Neither claim could be verified. Each side generally exaggerates
the other's casualties.
   Amani said insurgents fired rockets and artillery at the city
and airport, but the armed forces responded quickly.
   Jalalabad was the first major guerrilla target after Soviet
military forces completed their withdrawal from Afghanistan on Feb.
15, ending nine years of involvement in the civil war. When the
attack began nearly three months ago, some guerrilla commanders
predicted the city would fall within days.
   Capturing Jalalabad, about 45 miles from the border with
Pakistan, would give the insurgents a base for the interim
government they formed in February.
   Amani said about 18,000 soldiers had been deployed around
Jalalabad to fight an estimated 22,000 rebels surrounding the city.
   Gulbuddin Hekmatyar, who leads the fundamentalist Hezb-e-Islami
guerrilla group, said Monday in Pakistan the war would continue
until the Marxist government in Kabul falls.
   Addressing a news conference in Islamabad, Hekmatyar said his
followers would not accept a political solution involving King
Zahir Shah, who was overthrown in 1973 and lives in exile in Italy.
   In Kabul, Amani said insurgents fired rockets Sunday into Khost,
southern Afghanista, killing two civilians. He claimed 30
guerrillas were killed and 20 wounded.
   He said rockets killed three civilians in Kandahar and gave
guerrilla casualties there as seven killed and five wounded.
   Amani reported a civilian wounded in Herat, western Afghanistan,
and three insurgents killed in Konduz, a northern province.
