<DOCNO> AP890529-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-29-89 1426EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SummitScene     05-29 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Summit Scene,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sharpshooters, Monks, Motorcades Share Stage at NATO Summit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<UNK>By RAF CASERT ^Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Choppers whir overhead, sharpshooters
eye the roads, a bomb squad is on standby and Buddhist monks are
beating the drum for peace. It's summit time again in Brussels.
   Residents have seen it all before and hardly raise an eyebrow to
what has become a routine of pomp, protection and protest.
   But with the leaders of the 16 nations of the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization collected in a single building, security
officials are ever-vigilant.
   At least once a year, this capital of 1 million people also
hosts a top meeting for the heads of the 12-nation European
Economic Community trade bloc. Not surprisingly, people no longer
line the streets for a fleeting glimpse of world politics.
   ``For Belgium, there is a certain routine now,'' said a foreign
affairs official, who asked not to be named. ``Many summits have
identical procedures.''
   For weeks now the different police forces, the army and the
embassies of attending nations have had coordination meetings at
the interior ministry to pave the way for a safe summit.
   ``Nothing is left to chance,'' said a Brussels police official,
who also demanded anonymity. ``Holidays are suspended; everybody is
mobilized.''
   On Monday morning, security was at its tightest at the NATO
complex when a steady stream of black and gray limousines,
accompanied by hundreds of police motorcycles, swept through the
morning rush hour to deliver their guests for the first session.
   As President Bush arrived, sharpshooters stood on the roof of
the sprawling NATO complex next to men using binoculars to spot any
sign of trouble. For safe measure, a helicopter passed overhead.
   Within the barracks-like compound, hundreds of police and army
officials were posted along the different roads leading to the
meeting rooms and a bomb disposal squad was discreetly stationed
outside the main building.
   Journalists entered through a special side entrance equipped
with metal detecters. All equipment was checked before the
reporters got close to the headquarters.
   Outside, security forces kept watch on a peace demonstration of
a dozen Japanese Buddhist monks, who prayed and beat drums almost
throughout the morning, discreetly across the street.
   The security operation spans most of Brussels, from NATO
headquarters in suburban Brussels to the international airport on
the outskirts.
   Security also was tight at the 18th century Chateau Stuyvenberg,
where Bush is staying on the outskirts of Brussels. The president
was accompanied by three Secret Service agents when he went jogging
on the grounds for 20 minutes during an evening break.
   Leading up to the summit, bomb-sniffing dogs checked the
dignitaries' travel routes and accommodations. Several temporary
walls were even built to protect high-profile visitors such as Bush.
   At the coordination meetings, cooperation between local police
and security staff of attending nations had to be smoothed out to
avoid embarrassing scuffles between officials trying to protect the
same people, officials said.
   During the summit, well over 1,300 police and state police
worked round-the-clock.
   ``Obviously, it all costs a lot of money,'' said Frank De Mot of
the interior ministry. He and other officials said they were unable
to estimate the total expense.
   Hosting summits ``has disadvantages but also advantages,'' said
De Mot to explain Belgium's policy. It gives Brussels prestige and
provides the tourist industry with considerable income during the
summit.
   A summit also allows the police services to bask in the light of
global publicity and the competition is tough for the privilege to
escort leaders such as Bush or French President Francois Mitterrand.
   ``We really have to be diplomatic to resolve'' such quarrels,
said one official.
   Escorting the world leaders around Brussels ``is something that
you can always tell your children and grandchildren about,'' said
U.S. Embassy spokesman Jim Findlay.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
