<FILEID>AP-NR-05-29-89 1427EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Ethnic     05-29 0708</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Ethnic,0728</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deputies Use Congress to Air Ethnic Issues</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ethnic groups and Soviet republics fighting for
more independence are using the televised proceedings of the new
parliament to bring their diverse demands before a national
audience for the first time.
   On Monday, deputies from two areas that have been the most vocal
in demanding more independence _ the Baltic republics and the
southern republic of Georgia _ used the questioning of Vice
President Anatoly I. Lukyanov to present demands striking at the
very unity of this vast nation.
   Tamaz V. Gamkrelidze, a university professor, demanded the
Congress of People's Deputies condemn the ``annexation of the
independent democratic Georgian republic'' by the Red Army in 1921,
saying it violated a 1920 treaty agreed to by Soviet founder
Vladimir I. Lenin.
   For the Baltics, Lithuanian prosecutor Egidius V. Bichkauskas
questioned Lukyanov about the 1939 pact between Soviet Foreign
Minister Vyacheslav Molotov and German counterpart Joachim von
Ribbentrop.
   ``As a result of this pact, sovereign Lithuania and the other
Baltic republics were occupied and incorporated into the Soviet
Union, losing their independent statehood,'' Bichkauskas noted.
   Lukyanov replied only by saying the consequences of the
Soviet-German pact is under study by a review commission.
   Both the Georgian and Lithuanian deputies implied that the
Soviet Union, made up of 15 republics, was created in part by force
and against the will of the people in their republics.
   Groups from the Caucasian and Baltic republics have increased
contact with one another in recent months to intensify pressure for
more sovereignty over their own affairs.
   Such radical demands have been echoed in more muted tones in
other regions, particularly the Central Asian republics of
Uzbekistan, Tadzhikistan and Kirgizia.
   Lone Central Asian deputies, such as Vladimir Zolotukhin from
Tashkent, have complained their delegations were manipulated by
party and other chiefs.
   Generally, however, the Central Asian delegates have been part
of what historian Yuri Afanasyev labeled the ``aggressively
obedient majority,'' lauding Gorbachev and unanimously supporting
the leadership.
   Moscow and Leningrad progressives scathingly jest about this
behavior, prompting Kazakh delegate Galina Amangeldinova to
announce Monday: ``I am afraid to sit with the Moscow delegation.''
   There also have been fierce exchanges between delegates from
Armenia and Azerbaijan, two southern republics in bitter conflict
over the fate of Nagorno-Karabakh, an area within Azerbaijan with a
predominantly Armenian population.
   The ethnic conflict, which has sparked fatal rioting in the
republics, boiled to the surface on Thursday, when Armenian artist
Genrikh Igityan demanded public condemnation the February 1988 riot
in Sumgait in which 31 Armenians were killed. He said the deaths in
the Azerbaijani city should receive the same attention several
delegates from various regions gave the use of special anti-riot
forces in Tbilisi.
   Muslum Mamedov, Communist Party leader in Azerbaijan's capital,
Baku, shot back angrily that ``we have never sought confrontation''
and charged, without mentioning specifics, that Armenians also had
killed Azerbaijanis.
   In the commotion over the more well-known ethnic conflicts,
demands from smaller Soviet peoples have passed largely unnoticed.
   Khamzat A. Fargiev, a representative of the 100,000 Ingushes
living on the edge of Gorbachev's home region of Stavropol, used
Monday's debate to reiterate what he said were two unanswered
petitions for an independent Ingush region.
   Each petition has been supported by more than 60,000 Ingushes,
he noted, adding that his people also support demands from Volga
Germans and Crimean Tartars for restoration of a measure of their
independence. They were among the minority groups deported from
their homes under Josef Stalin.
   ``This is the next national crisis,'' Fargiev warned of the
problem of the Ingushes, whose conflicts with Chechens, Ossetians
and other neighboring peoples led authorities in 1984 to bring in
special security forces and impose a curfew in the regional center
of Ordzhonokidze.
   His prediction drew far less attention than a semiserious jibe
from a Siberian delegate over the age-old Russian practice of
sending criminals and inefficient officials to his bleak region.
   ``Please, don't send any more of that scum to us in Siberia,''
pleaded writer Roman X. Solntsev amid general laughter from the
floor. Lukyanov gravely thanked him for the remark, noting that
``there are whole regions'' in Siberia where ``it's difficult to
restore order.''
</TEXT>
