<FIRST>r i AM-Panama     05-29 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Memorial Day Observations at Canal Cemetery</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Memorial Day Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT COROZAL, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Men and women of the Armed Forces
and the U.S. Embassy observed Memorial Day with a small group of
Panamanians at a cemetery dedicated in part to those who
``contributed to the construction, operation and security of the
Panama Canal.''
   At a sun-baked hilltop monument surrounded by palm trees and
purple and orange tropical flowers, about 150 people listened to
speeches, prayed and watched as Air Force A-37 Dragonflies flew
over in a ``missing man'' formation.
   The only mention of the political crisis that has brought 1,900
new U.S. troops to canal installations came when Rear Adm. Gerald
E. Gnecknow noted that a Marine who died last year was among those
being honored.
   Cpl. Ricardo M. Villahermosa of Santurce, Puerto Rico, was
killed by fellow Marine guards on April 11, 1988, at a fuel storage
depot as they tried to surround what they described as a group of
intruders.
   The Panamanian Defense Forces denied there was an intrusion and
said the death caused by trigger-happy U.S. troops.
   Gnecknow, the Southern Command naval chief, offered a brief
history of Memorial Day since the Civil War, with special mention
of the explosion that killed 47 people aboard the USS Iowa, which
he once commanded.
   ``I've come every year since we moved back four years ago,''
said Ed Figueroa, a U.S. citizen who was born in the former Canal
Zone and now works for General Electric.
   He and his wife, Blanca, put a spray of carnations on his
father's grave. Marcelo Figueroa was from Puerto Rico, moved to
Panama in 1920 and served in both World War I and World War II.
   ``I've come every year since I was a little girl. I like the
band, I like the colors,'' said a middle-aged Panamanian woman who
refused to give her name. She said her husband worked for the
Panama Canal Commission.
   A gray-haired man said he was looking for his brother's grave _
he was in the Army and died on duty at Fort Amador, a former U.S.
canal installation. He, too, refused to give his name.
   ``You've got to be careful these days,'' he said.
   Most of the 30 Panamanians stood along a road below the hilltop.
A few Panamanian Cub Scouts saluted both the Panamanian and U.S.
national anthems.
   The Corozal American Cemetery, containing nearly 5,000 graves,
was established in 1904, when the United States started
constructing the canal. Treaties call for the 17-acre section where
Americans are interred to be maintained by the American Battle
Monuments Commission even after the United States cedes the canal
to Panama at the end of 1999.
   Elsewhere in Panama, Monday was an ordinary working day.
Panamanian newspapers attacked U.S. motives in calling for the
ouster of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega. Teachers began preparations
for a school year that begins on June 5, two weeks late after being
postponed because of civil unrest following Panama's nullified May
7 presidential election.
   The latest joke making the rounds concerned the advice given to
a foreign correspondent who wanted to see the end of Noriega's
rule: ``Buy a house.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890529-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-29-89 1443EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Bush-Negotiator     05-29 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Negotiator,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Negotiator Endorses Plan but Questions Timetable</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former U.S. arms control director Ralph
Earle II praised President Bush's proposal Monday to cut NATO and
Warsaw Pact non-nuclear forces, but said he doubts work on a treaty
can be completed in six months to a year.
   Earle, who negotiated the 1979 Strategic Arms Limitation Treaty
with the Soviet Union for the Carter administration, said Bush's
timetable is ``overly optimistic.''
   In an interview, the former U.S. official also foresaw potential
problems in defining combat aircraft and other weapons and a
possible attempt by Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev to
include naval forces.
   The North Atlantic Treaty Organization has an edge over the
Warsaw Pact in combat ships in Europe, Earle said.
   ``No matter how much political will, there are going to be
substantial problems,'' Earle said.
   He predicted it would take two years to complete negotiations in
the Conventional Forces in Europe talks in Vienna.
   Earle praised Bush for putting the stress on conventional forces
instead of nuclear wepaons as the most important disarmament issue
in Europe.
   He said the Bush plan is ``achievable,'' but could have gone
further to ease tensions if the president also had proposed
withdrawal of tanks and other powerful weapons from the East-West
divide. He said such a disarmament corridor could help avert a
conflict between East and West.
