<FILEID>AP-NR-05-29-89 1450EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Palme     05-29 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Palme,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Indict Suspect in Palme Murder</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors indicted a man with a
violent criminal past Monday for the murder of Prime Minister Olof
Palme, who was shot down on a snowy street in Stockholm more than
three years ago.
   The 3,000 pages of evidence in the indictment outlined a case
against Carl Gustav Christer Pettersson, 42, that relied heavily on
the testimony of Palme's widow, Lisbet, and other witnesses who put
the defendant at the scene.
   The Palmes were walking home from a movie the night of Feb. 28,
1986, without bodyguards, when the killer fired from close range
and fled into a side street.
   ``He fits my description. The outline of his face, his eyes and
the terrifying face,'' the indictment quoted Mrs. Palme as telling
investigators.
   In addition to first degree murder, Pettersson is charged with
the attempted murder of Mrs. Palme, who was slightly wounded.
   Pettersson has denied killing Palme.
   His attorney, Arne Liljefors, said the prosecution had not
provided a motive or forensic evidence to support the charges.
Pettersson was arrested Dec. 14 in a twist to a case which that
focused on possible international conspiracies.
   Police and security agencies had been accused of bungling the
case and failing to turn up credible leads despite a reward of 50
million kronor ($8 million). Three police chiefs and a justice
minister resigned at various points in the investigation.
   Palme, a dynamic and controversial politician, was a U.N.
mediator in the Iran-Iraq war and an advocate of world disarmament.
He led Social Democratic governments in Sweden for 11 years.
   Prosecutors said 33 witnesses would support their case that
Pettersson followed the Palmes down Sveavagen Boulevard, and some
would testify he had access to a weapon and lied about his
whereabouts.
   Liljefors, the defense lawyer, indicated he would question the
credibility of witnesses testifying three years after the crime.
Prosecutor Jorgen Almbland said of the evidence: ``I am convinced
this is enough to win a conviction.'' According to the indictment,
Mrs. Palme said ``she thought it was youngsters playing with
firecrackers'' when she heard the shots, ``and she turned toward
her husband to comment.''
   ``At the same moment he collapsed, badly bleeding from his chest
and mouth,'' it said. ``Mrs. Palme heard another bang and felt a
burning sensation in her back.''
   She saw a running man, who stopped briefly and turned to face
her before continuing to flee, the indictment said.
   ``He was in his 40s, around 180 centimeters (6 feet) tall, with
a compact body and short neck,'' Mrs. Palme was quoted as saying.
``He was dark, but not like from southern lands.''
   Pettersson, a drug and alcohol addict, has a record of more than
60 crimes, including a conviction for stabbing a man to death with
a bayonet.
   He was questioned and released in the first weeks of the
investigation, but called in again last year when police discovered
holes in his alibi.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
