<DOCNO> AP890529-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-29-89 1513EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MosaicsTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0551 05-29 0870</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mosaics Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0551,0890</SECOND>
<HEAD>Art World Keeping Eye on Indiana Court This Week</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `Cyprus claims...', to CORRECT date of Turkish
invasion to 1974 sted 1975.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JODI PERRAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A trial that starts this week pitting an
Indianapolis art dealer against the rival Greek and Turkish
governments of Cyprus could have repercussions throughout the world
for claims to national art treasures.
   Art dealer Peg Goldberg is being sued over four sixth-century
mosaics that some call the most important Christian antiquities
ever to come on the market. Cypriot authorities claim they were
ripped from the walls of a village church.
   If U.S. District Judge James E. Noland rules for Goldberg,
millions of dollars worth of plundered antiquities could pour into
this country, some analysts predict.
   ``Lawyers for American collectors, both institutional and
private, will be watching this for its implications,'' said
Constance Lowenthal, executive director of the International
Foundation for Art Research in New York.
   ``American collections do have many antiquities whose origins
are unclear. It's an important case. The stakes are high and the
implications could be very broad.''
   In March, the Republic of Cyprus and the Autocephalous Greek
Orthodox Church of Cyprus sued Goldberg and her dealership,
Goldberg and Feldman Fine Arts of suburban Carmel.
   Cyprus claims the mosaics were taken illegally to Europe from
Lythrankomi in 1979. The village is under the control of a
breakaway Turkish government that has ruled the northern third of
the war-torn island nation since 1974.
   The self-designated Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus entered
the fray on Wednesday when it filed a request to intervene in the
lawsuit and claimed it is the rightful owner of the mosaics. Turkey
is the only country that recognizes the Turkish occupation state.
   Joseph D. Youssouf, a New Jersey lawyer representing Turkish
Cyprus, said his client was eager to argue its case in court.
   ``Who is the Republic of Cyprus, who are the Turkish Cypriots
and who owns the mosaics are all interrelated questions,'' Youssouf
said. ``There's an awful lot at stake.''
   The mosaics, analysts say, are among only a relative handful of
artworks surviving from the first centuries of Christianity.
Fragments of a much larger work at Panagia Kanakaria church, they
depict heads of Christ as a boy, the apostles James and Matthew and
an archangel. The four pieces are each roughly 2 feet square.
   ``These mosaics, priceless examples of Byzantine art, are
irreplaceable aspects of our country's cultural heritage,'' said
Michael Kyprianou, a deputy state attorney general of Cyprus.
   Goldberg, 50, who usually deals in 19th and 20th century
American and European art, said she knew she was onto something big
when she first viewed the mosaics in Geneva, Switzerland, last June.
   ``I had some suspicions as I looked at them and my heart
stopped. I thought they were possibly extraordinarily important,
regardless of whatever else was proven in my mind,'' she said.
   ``We've been told they would be the most important Christian
antiquities ever to come on the market.''
   Goldberg claims she researched the legal status of the mosaics
before purchasing them in July for $1.1 million from Aydin Dikmen,
who said he was the former official archaeologist for Turkish
Cyprus. She has offered them for sale for $20 million, but they're
not on the market pending the outcome of the suit.
   According to Youssouf, Dikmen is a fraud and so were the customs
and shipping documents he produced for Goldberg.
   No U.S. law or treaty applies to the case. The United States and
Cyprus have both signed a UNESCO convention on stolen artworks, but
it does not apply here to properties removed from their home
country before 1983.
   The case could rest on two questions: Was Goldberg a good-faith
purchaser of the mosaics, as required by Swiss law, and was the
Republic of Cyprus diligent in trying to get the mosaics back?
   Under Swiss law, a sale is legal if the buyer acts openly and in
the good-faith belief that the item was obtained legally,
regardless of whether the seller legitimately owns the article.
   The law has made Switzerland a hotbed for international art
transactions.
   As for Cyprus' efforts to get back the mosaics, the government's
antiquities department notified museums in 1980 the mosaics were
gone. Two years later, the Cyprus Embassy in Washington issued a
news release.
   But Ms. Lowenthal said her foundation, which keeps files on
30,000 stolen artworks, was never notified.
   ``We're not so famous in the Mediterranean, but if a government
was eager to spread the word to all possible agencies, it would not
take them very long to discover our existence,'' she said.
   For now, the mosaics are in an Indianapolis bank vault.
   Walter Hopps, director of the Menil Collection in Houston, who
last year solved a similar problem through a loan agreement with
Cyprus, said the lawsuit will become a test case.
   ``If the courts uphold the legality of the entry, if there's
even a window of time where it looks like it might stand, then the
possibility exists that millions and millions of dollars worth of
plundered antiquities will pour into the United States,'' he said.
``It will be a horrible precedent.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
