<FIRST>u i AM-Cyprus-Rockets     05-29 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cyprus-Rockets,0599</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Find Arms Cache, Arrest Lebanese</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LARNACA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said Monday they found an arms
cache that included shoulder-fired missiles they believe were to be
used against Lebanese army helicopters, possibly one carrying Gen.
Michel Aoun, the Christian leader.
   Andreas Potamaris, assistant police chief, said six Lebanese men
were arrested. He quoted one as saying: ``We came to Cyprus to
clear up our inter-Lebanese accounts.''
   Five of the suspects arrived illegally in two rubber dinghies,
police said.
   The carefully wrapped missiles were found 150 yards offshore,
about half a mile from the Larnaca airport apron the helicopters
use for daily flights between Cyprus and Lebanon.
   Police said the plot was uncovered when scuba divers found the
two Soviet-designed SAM-7 missiles and launchers Sunday on a reef
in about six feet of water. Only the firing mechanisms were missing.
   Aoun had been scheduled to go through the airport last week on
his way to an Arab League summit in Morocco, where Arab leaders
were discussing the 14-year-old Lebanese civil war, but did not
make the trip.
   Potamaris said police raided a beachfront apartment Monday and
found the dinghies, five Kalashnikov assault rifles, 13 magazines
of ammunition, 28 grenades, two limpet mines and the firing
mechanisms for the rockets.
   Although the targets had not been confirmed, he said, ``one can
draw an inference from the fact that the rocket launchers were
found less than a kilometer from the Larnaca airport apron, where
the helicopters of the Christian Lebanese army come and go daily.''
   Interior Minister Christodoulos Veniamin said on television the
target was an ``Arab personality'' who was to arrive by helicoptr,
but he did not elaborate.
   ``They planned to commit a crime on the soil of Cyprus and this
of course is unacceptable,'' he said. ``We are not sure yet what
they say is true because we just started the investigation.''
   Police sources said privately it may have been Aoun, whose
Christian army units have been fighting a Moslem alliance of
Syrians and Druse militiamen since early March.
   Two days before the missiles were discovered, police detained a
Lebanese for wandering through this southern port in a suspicious
manner. They found that Salam Khafasi did not have an entry stamp
in his passport.
   Through him, police found the other suspects and the apartment.
The other five arrested were identified as Tawfik Wadih Ashaar,
Idris Jamal Jaber, Wadih Salim Salamon, Rostom Najib Sirhan and
Emil Gharali.
   Police said Gharali, picked up Friday after Khafasi's arrest,
was the only one to enter Cyprus legally.
   Photographers were allowed to take pictures of the suspects, but
when asked why they were in Cyprus the men shouted: ``Get away! We
can't tell you anything!''
   In September, police found the tripod base for a Milan anti-tank
missile launcher on the Larnaca airport outskirts, but were unable
to determine who put it there or why.
   Omar Ahmed Hawwilo, a 28-year-old Lebanese, was sentenced to 15
years in prison last year for trying to blow up the Israeli Embassy
in Nicosia with a car bomb. It exploded 200 yards from the embassy
on May 11, 1988, killing the driver and two Cypriots and wounding
people.
   Three senior Palestine Liberation Organization guerrilla officrs
were killed by a car bomb in February 1988 at Limassol port in
southeern Cyprus. A ferry scheduled to carry Palestinians on a
protest voyage to Israel was disabled by a limpet mine the day
before.
</TEXT>
