<FIRST>r a AM-VicksburgShooting     05-29 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vicksburg Shooting,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Six Bystanders Shot When Drug Deal Goes Sour, Police Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VICKSBURG, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six bystanders were wounded, including a
young woman who remained in critical condition Monday, after a hail
of semi-automatic gunfire erupted outside a local bar when an
apparent drug deal went bad, police said.
   The six people were wounded Sunday morning in a drive-by
shooting outside the Dodge City Disco, said Detective Sgt. Mitchell
Dent of the Vicksburg Police Department. None was thought to be
involved in the deal, Dent said.
   Two remained hospitalized Monday.
   Three people were charged with aggravated assault and remained
in the Warren County Jail on Monday under $100,000 bonds each.
   The three were identified as Rosemarie Hogan, 24, of Vicksburg;
Martin D. Scrivner, 30, of Sulphur, La.; and Johnny R. Mowdy, 27,
of Canton. Each was charged with six counts of aggravated assault.
   Four of the wounded were treated and released from Mercy
Regional Medical Center. Sheila Carter, 20, was in critical but
stable condition, said hospital spokeswoman Jamie Segura. The other
hospitalized person, an 18-year-old woman, was in good condition
Monday.
   Police were still investigating the case, Dent said. But he said
it appears that an incident earlier at the bar involved a drug deal
that went sour.
   Dent said Mowdy, Scrivner and Hogan allegedly returned to the
bar as it was closing early Sunday, drove by in a van and sprayed
those standing outside the club with gunfire.
   They were arrested a short time after the shootings in a van
matching witnesses' description of the one involved in the
shooting. A semiautomatic rifle was found in the van.
   The Dodge City Disco is a predominately black bar where police
have made several drug arrests previously, Dent said. The three
charged with the shooting are white.
</TEXT>
