<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Yeltsin     05-29 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Yeltsin,0635</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yeltsin Leads Jubilant Victory March</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MOSB6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Well-wishers hung from trees and tossed red roses
Monday as thousands of people marched behind populist Boris N.
Yeltsin in a spontaneous celebration of his stunning appointment to
the nation's new legislature.
   The 58-year-old firebrand was besieged by a roaring and
deliriously happy mass of supporters after he left the Kremlin,
where the Congress of People's Deputies had just given him a seat
in the new legislature, the Supreme Soviet.
   Yeltsin had failed to win enough votes in the Congress, a newly
created 2,250 parliament, to win election to the Supreme Soviet, a
full-time legislature that has been given broad powers.
   But one candidate who was elected by the Congress agreed to
resign to open a seat for Yeltsin _ a reformer considered perhaps
the most popular figure behind President Mikhail S. Gorbachev _ and
the Congress overwhelmingly agreed.
   The action came one day after thousands had protested Yeltsin's
defeate.
   ``Hooray! Hooray!'' Soviets shouted as they joined the towering,
silver-haired man from Sverdlovsk in a spontaneous victory march
through central Moscow.
   Most had learned of his victory from the live television and
radio broadcasts of the Congress session, but one incredulous
pedestrian asked the boisterous entourage, ``Is it really true?''
   ``Congratulations!'' yelled others who greeted Yeltsin as he
walked from the Kremlin and then along Gorky Street, one of
Moscow's busiest thoroughfares. ``All the people are with you,''
one man yelled to Yeltsin, who wore a blue-gray suit and towered
above the crowd.
   Anna Sabalova, with tears of joy in her eyes, told a reporter:
   ``We knew he was an honest person. We knew he was elected by
millions but that just a few in the Congress had held him back.''
   A city bus driver stopped after apparently spotting Yeltsin on a
sidewalk in front of the Kremlin. He honked his horn rhythmically,
and dozens of passengers got off to join the procession.
   It was a display of the kind of people power that gave Yeltsin
89 percent of the vote in citywide Moscow elections in March to the
Congress.
   Yeltsin smiled broadly and thanked supporters as he made his way
through the crush during a one-hour march to Pushkin Square, a
popular site for demonstrations where an estimated 5,000 people
gathered.
   Women kissed him, men shook his hand, and he carried red
carnations and pink roses given him by supporters.
   At the square, Yeltsin told a crowd of thousands _ some perched
on trees to get a glance of their new legislator _ that his
appointment was a ``victory by the people over the secret apparatus.
   ``I thank you for your faith,'' Yeltsin, using a megaphone, told
the jubilant crowd. He wound up the rally with his hands held above
his head in a gesture of victory.
   Even Yegor K. Ligachev, Yeltsin's conservative foe on the ruling
Politburo, was unusually conciliatory.
   ``It was democratic. It was just,'' Ligachev told reporters. ``I
have one way of looking at things, and he has another. The
important thing is to stick to party comradeship.''
   Yeltsin and Ligachev have clashed several times. After
criticizing the slow pace of Soviet reform and naming Ligachev as a
cause in October 1987, Yeltsin was fired as Moscow party chief and
lost his own non-voting seat on the Politburo.
   Human rights campaigner Andrei D. Sakharov, a Congress deputy,
said in an interview that Yeltsin's elevation marked a
``restoration of justice,'' although he said it was not
accomplished smoothly.
   Yeltsin, with a wide smile, told reporters as he left the
session his appointment showed the Congress was becoming
``gradually more democratic.''
</TEXT>
