<DOCNO> AP890529-0116 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-29-89 1627EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Seabrook-Tests     05-29 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Seabrook-Tests,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seabrook Operators Start Low-Power Testing Process</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEABROOK, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The process of heating up the reactor at
the Seabrook nuclear power plant reached its first major step
Monday as operators prepare the controversial plant for its first
low-power testing.
   The first atomic chain reaction, expected within seven to 10
days, will be the biggest milestone yet for a plant that is a
decade behind schedule, billions of dollars over budget and a focus
of the nation's anti-nuclear movement.
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission gave Seabrook its low-power
license last Friday. The heating process began Saturday, and on
Monday morning, the water in the reactor's cooling system reached
200 degrees.
   ``Everything's going smoothly and as planned,'' Seabrook
spokesman Ron Sher said. ``We want to conduct low-power tests as
soon as possible to make sure there are no adjustements we need to
make to the plant.''
   The reactor must reach 557 degrees, expected to take five days,
before preparations can begin to start the nuclear chain reaction
in the 100 tons of uranium fuel.
   Nearly three years after the reactor was completed, the $6
billion project surmounted most obstacles to win NRC approval for
the tests on May 18. But the commission granted a one-week stay of
the license so a federal court could rule on requests to delay the
tests.
   Last Thursday, the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the
District of Columbia declined to delay the tests, and the low-power
license was issued Friday by the NRC's Office of Nuclear Reactor
Regulation.
   The license will let Seabrook conduct atomic tests at up to 5
percent of full power. The plant must win final federal approval
for evacuation plans for nearby communities before it could operate
commercially.
   Evacuation in case of emergency is the major issue raised by
opponents of the plant, who say communities in the area couldn't
possibly be evacuated soon enough.
   Late Saturday, plant operators began opening valves and rapidly
circulating 100,000 gallons of water through the reactor coolant
system. The reactor is heated by the friction of that fast-water
circulation.
   After the reactor reaches 557 degrees, operators will have to
calibrate instruments and perform other tests before they can
remove control rods from the reactor core and dilute the boron
concentration in the reactor coolant water.
   The boron and control rods absorb neutrons from decaying uranium
atoms, preventing them from striking other uranium atoms and
starting a chain reaction. Removing them allows the neutrons to
split uranium atoms and begin a self-sustained nuclear chain
reaction.
   There would be about seven days of tests, at power levels
ranging from 0.01 percent to 3 percent of the reactor's capacity.
After those tests, the reactor would be cooled down again until the
next step in the fight over whether the plant will go into
operation or be scrapped.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
