<FIRST>r a AM-MysteryFlower     05-29 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mystery Flower,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mystery Person Leaves Flower On Grave For 17th Consecutive Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Memorial Day Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOPLIN, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the 17th consecutive Memorial Day, a pink
rose was left on Polly Scantlin's grave in a Joplin cemetery and
her family has no idea who is responsible.
   Ms. Scantlin, who lived in the area most of her life, was 81
when she died in 1971. Pink roses were Ms. Scantlin's favorite, and
before she died she asked for an arrangement of them at her
funeral, said her daughter, Dora Miller.
   Ms. Scantlin's family has tried for years to determine who sends
the flower, even staking out the grave on the Friday before
Memorial Day to watch for the deliverer. But a bouquet of pink
roses or a single rose always was already on the grave.
   Caretakers of the Ozark Memorial Park Cemetery say they have no
clues, either.
   ``We don't have any idea who it is,'' says Mrs. Miller. ``I
would ask everybody I would see, `Have you put those flowers on
Mama's grave?' I have asked people for years.
   ``I've asked all the family. I've asked all the friends.''
   Ms. Scantlin's husband died in 1972, and most of her friends are
dead. Her only other living child, a daughter in Arkansas, also has
no idea who sends the flower.
</TEXT>
