<FIRST>r a AM-CivilWarReburial     05-29 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Civil War Reburial,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Forgotten Civil War Soldiers Buried In National Cemetery</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Memorial Day Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEAUFORT, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To the beat of muffled drums and the sound
of a fife, the remains of 19 black Union soldiers lost since the
Civil War were escorted Monday to their final resting place in a
National Cemetery.
   The remains, unearthed two years ago during road construction at
Folly Beach, S.C., are those of members of the 54th and 55th
Massachusetts Regiment and the 1st North Carolina Infantry
Regiment, three black units that fought for the North in the Civil
War.
   The Massachusetts regiments were the first Union regiments
formed with volunteer black troops.
   The soldiers were believed killed during a July 18, 1863,
assault on Fort Wagner, outside Charleston, S.C., although they
also may have died of disease.
   They had been buried in a military cemetery within the Union
encampment outside Fort Wagner, but the burial ground apparently
was neglected and forgotten after the war.
   Among those at the Memorial Day ceremony were Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis and two men whose forefathers fought in the
Massachusetts regiments. The three laid a wreath in front of the
coffins, laid out in three rows.
   More than 4,000 people gathered at an edge of the cemetery
beneath three sprawling oak trees.
   ``Here we hear not only the voices of Massahcusetts' past and
the cannon of Fort Wagner, but the warm promise of our nation; of
the blood of its men and women, black and white, alive with a love
of our beautiful land,'' Dukakis said.
   ``This issue of black men fighting for the Union Army was highly
controversial at the time. I'm proud to say they were supported by
the people of Massachusetts,'' Dukakis said.
   The remains were buried in accordance with 1863 Army regulations
and the coffins were covered with a 34-star American flag. The
Massachusetts state flag also was draped on each coffin.
   They were escorted to the burial site at the National Cemetery
in Beaufort by actors dressed as Union soldiers from the movie
``Glory,'' about the 54th Massachusetts Regiment, which recently
completed filming near Savannah, Ga.
   Soil from Massachusetts was sprinkled onto the coffins.
   ``The black soldiers of the Massachusetts 54th and 55th
Regiments were fighting for their own liberty, to grasp their own
freedom and to ensure both for others of their own race,'' Dukakis
said.
   Deputy state archeologist Steven Smith said other members of the
Massachusetts regiments also are buried in the cemetery. He said
they died at the Civil War battle of Honey Hill about 12 miles from
Beaufort.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
