<HEAD>Man on Marshals Service's 15 Most-wanted List Captured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RAPID CITY, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A killer on the U.S. Marshals Service's
15 most-wanted list was captured Monday after he fled from a
roadblock on the Pine Ridge Indian Reservation, authorities said.
    James Weddell, 33, of Wagner, was serving an 80-year
manslaughter sentence for beating a man to death when he escaped
from a maximum-security prison in Sioux Falls on May 26, 1987, with
five other inmates. The others were captured.
   Weddell was in a car that was stopped at the roadblock.
   ``The Pine Ridge Police Department was stopping cars coming back
from some kind of a band concert ... that they'd had down there,''
said Bob Leighton, a deputy U.S. marshal from Rapid City.
   When authorities got the driver and two passengers out of one
car, someone jumped into the driver's seat and sped away in the
car, Leighton said.
   ``One of the people said, `There goes Weddell,' and they took
off and pursued the vehicle,'' he said.
   The driver abandoned the car and ran to a creek bottom. Police
searched and found Weddell, who had a weapon but did not fire it.
   Weddell was being held in the Pennington County Jail in Rapid
City until a scheduled court appearance Tuesday morning.
