<FIRST>r a AM-Volcano     05-29 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Volcano,0226</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kilauea Volcano Turns on Homes for First Time in a Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KALAPANA, Hawaii (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kilauea, the world's most active
volcano, has begun ravaging private property again after a
year-long quiet spell.
   The volcano destroyed four houses in May, for a total of 68
houses destroyed since Kilauea's latest eruption began more than
six years ago.
   Oozing lava overtook the 68th home Saturday, and on Sunday cut
off the only road to 21 surviving homes in the Royal Gardens
subdivision, said Hawaii County Civil Defense Administrator Harry
Kim. He said all residents were evacuated before the road was cut.
   For most of the past year, lava flowing to the Pacific Ocean had
been hidden from sight. It was confined inside tubes hidden beneath
the gray moonscape of hardened lava that cuts a two-mile-wide swath
through the otherwise lush Puna coastline on Hawaii Island.
   But the tubes became partially blocked earlier this month and
forced lava into the mostly rural subdivision, which has been
devastated since the eruption began in January 1983, scientists
said.
   Approximately 40 percent of Kilauea's daily lava output of
500,000 cubic meters was creeping through the lower portion of
Royal Gardens, which stretches up a slope overlooking the island's
southeast coast, said Reggie Okamura, a spokesman for the U.S.
Geological Survey's Hawaiian Volcano Observatory.
</TEXT>
