<FIRST>r i AM-Yeltsin-Profile     05-29 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yeltsin-Profile,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yeltsin Rouses People With Righteous Fury</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MOSB6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Populist Boris N. Yeltsin, a self-described
childhood hooligan, has struck on a formula for political survival:
turn hard talk about economic reform into popular acclaim.
   Before being resurrected again from political defeat Monday, he
used a recent interview to attack the leadership of his old mentor,
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, for ``inconsistency,
indecisiveness, half-measures.''
   Earlier this year, Yeltsin won nearly 90 percent of the vote for
his Moscow seat in the new Congress of People's Deputies by
accusing the Communist elite of wallowing in luxury while Soviets
scour the black market for basic items like soap.
   The burly, rubbery-faced 58-year-old, who was ousted from the
ruling Politburo in 1987, made his political comeback in a surprise
turnaround Monday by winning a seat on the working legislature
known as the Supreme Soviet. He was initially rejected, but a new
lawmaker stepped down to make space for Yeltsin _ all with
Gorbachev's blessing.
   Boris N. Yeltsin is once again a force to be reckoned with.
   Not everyone holds him for a hero, though. Some Baltic
independence activists see him as a reformer _ but not necessarily
an ally.
   And conservative Communist Party leaders demanded an
investigation of him when Yeltsin called for consideration of
multiple parties.
   This is not the first time Yeltsin has sown mischief. A
self-declared troublemaker as a child, he lost a thumb and
forefinger playing with a hand grenade.
   Eventually, however, he showed a preference for the
rough-and-tumble of Soviet politics. He served as regional
Communist Party boss in his hometown of Sverdlovsk in the Ural
mountains before Gorbachev brought him to Moscow in 1985.
   As the capital's party chief, he quickly moved to center stage
by fighting party privileges and catching managers holding back
scarce consumer goods for special customers.
   Sarcastic and authoritarian, he demanded a crackdown on
corruption and criticized rampant nepotism. Once, he revealed that
70 percent of the students at a prestigious institute were children
of ranking officials.
   His initial setback came in October 1987, when he took aim at
Politburo conservative Yegor K. Ligachev and Gorbachev himself at a
party meeting.
   He demanded faster reforms and charged that Gorbachev, his
mentor, received ``intolerable'' glorification. Stung party leaders
promptly fired Yeltsin from both the Moscow party job and the
non-voting spot on the Politburo.
   Typically, a disgraced Politburo member becomes a
``non-person,'' vanishing forever from the Soviet political scene.
But Yeltsin resurfaced within a week as a deputy construction
minister and remained one of the party's top 250 leaders on the
policy-making Central Committee.
   Now, even his old nemesis Ligachev, who shook with laughter over
Yeltsin's initial defeat for a seat on the Supreme Soviet, has
changed his tune. Ligachev told reporters Monday that it was only
fair that Yeltsin gain a seat.
</TEXT>
