<HEAD>Comedian Braves Freeway on Foot With Exit Lines for Exit Sign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bob Hope celebrated his 86th birthday on
the road Monday _ actually on the Ventura Freeway, where he
dedicated a sign for an exit to Bob Hope Drive.
   Standing in a fluorescent orange vest and a hardhat, the
comedian dispensed free one-liners as Memorial Day motorists roared
by on one of California's busiest highways.
   ``Now I'm a star of stage, screen, television and traffic
jams,'' Hope quipped in a telephone interview a few minutes before
he left for the freeway, a short drive from his Toluca Lake home.
``My mother always wanted me to be a doctor or an off-ramp.''
   ``It's appropriate,'' he added in another one-liner prepared for
the California Department of Transportation event. ``What audiences
always liked best about me was my exit.''
   The name of a short street beside NBC Studios in Burbank was
changed to Bob Hope Drive a year ago. And for many years travelers
in the Palm Springs area have had a chance to exit Interstate 10 to
another Bob Hope Drive in Rancho Mirage.
   ``This is some day,'' said Hope. ``After all, they closed all
the banks and the schools.''
   But seriously, despite his age, Hope's current schedule seems as
heavy as when he traveled the globe entertaining U.S. servicemen in
World War II, the Korean conflict and Vietnam.
   He'll be in Salt Lake City for an Indian Education Services
fund-raising golf tourney Tuesday, and leave home again Thursday on
a three-week trip that will include appearances, benefits, stage
shows and charity golf tournaments in the Eastern United States.
   Hope said he occasionally can shoot an 18-hole score below his
age on the golf course. ``But when I played yesterday, I shot my
license plate number.''
