<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador     05-29 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Urge Opposition To Promote Peace Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas asked the
political opposition Monday to help them arrange peace talks with
the new rightist government.
   The proposal was the fourth such overture since January. The
others have foundered because of what officials viewed as
unrealistic demands by the insurgents.
   The new offer said opposition parties should promote and sponsor
``dialogue until direct negotiation between the government and the
(rebel) FMLN is achieved.''
   The FMLN, or Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, made the
offer in a communique signed by two top commanders.
   President Jose Napoleon Duarte, a Christian Democrat who has
governed for five years, will transfer power Thursday to Alfredo
Cristiani of the rightist Republican Nationalist Alliance, or
Arena. He was elected in March.
   Despite their renewed call for talks, the rebels' communique
said, ``The installation of the Arena government means ... a
deepening and prolongation of war in El Salvador.''
   Moreover, the rebels made no concessions or major changes of
position from previous proposals.
   Cristiani had no immediate comment on the latest proposal. He
has said previously he is willing to talk to rebel representatives
but will not negotiate on power-sharing.
   Ricardo Alvarenga Valdivieso, president of Congress and Arena
director, reacted to the new proposal by telling reporters, ``There
are things that are done just so they will be rejected.''
   Among the demands, the rebels urged Arena to ensure the trial of
party founder and principal ideologue Roberto D'Aubuisson, a
cashiered army major accused of involvement in death squads and the
1980 slaying of Archbishop Monsignor Oscar Romero.
   It also demands that death squads be dismantled, that agrarian
reform be maintained, and that banks and sales of export crops be
nationalized.
   D'Aubuisson denies he ran death squads. The party says it has
nothing to do with such organizations.
   Cristiani says agrarian reform will not be rolled back, but he
says the private sector will have a dominant role in banking and
export.
   The guerrillas in turn promise not to kill Arena officials or
their family members or family members of military officers. They
also say they would stop blowing up utility poles in the city and
imposing nationwide road transport bans.
   More than 65,000 Salvadorans, mostly civilians, have been killed
in the civil war. The United States has supported the government.
</TEXT>
