<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0579 05-29 0765</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0579,0790</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cardinal O'Connor Concedes Trip Did Not Help Hostages</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout on later O'Connor news conference. No pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEI1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BKIRKI, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal John O'Connor of New York said
Monday that his trip to Lebanon did not help the nine American
hostages and nine other foreigners held here and he hoped to return
to try again.
   The Roman Catholic archbishop appealed three times to
pro-Iranian kidnappers after arriving Saturday to be allowed to
visit the Americans. He received no response.
   At his final 30-minute news conference Monday at the Bkirki
monastry north of Beirut, O'Connor said in reply to questions that
he did not know if acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss was a Christian
or a Moslem and that he was unsure of army commander Gen. Michel
Aoun's political role.
   He also said he was unaware of the religion of Aoun, who heads a
Christian military Cabinet vying for authority against Hoss'
Cabinet.
   O'Connor was expected to leave Tuesday for Cyprus by army
helicopter and to stop in Rome before returning to New York. Police
in Cyprus on Monday uncovered a plot to shoot down helicopters
coming from the Christian enclave.
   The prelate said Monday that if he offended anyone by canceling
a scheduled visit to Moslem west Beirut, ``I apologize to them.''
   The cancellation Sunday drew angry statements from Hoss, head of
the mostly Moslem Cabinet in Lebanon's dual government, and other
Moslem leaders.
   O'Connor said the decision was made because he was told there
was fighting along the Green Line that separates the capital into
Christian and Moslem sectors.
   ``The information I was given was inaccurate. There clearly was
no special problem,'' O'Connor said. He refused to say who gave him
the wrong information.
   A civil war has raged in Lebanon for more than 14 years.
   O'Connor's visit was an attempt to refocus attention on the
plight of the 18 foreigners missing and believed held hostage in
Lebanon. The issue has been overshadowed by 11 weeks of fighting.
   Terry Anderson, 41, chief Middle East correspondent of The
Associated Press, was kidnapped on March 16, 1985, and is the
longest held hostage.
   O'Connor said Monday: ``My time is running out. I have not been
able to learn anything about you (hostages). I hope I'll come back
and continue trying.''
   He said he sought through ``various people who might know if
they could give any idea of where the hostages might be ... I have
been given no leads whatsoever, no understanding of where they
might be.''
   O'Connor's last hostage appeal was made in an interview with the
AP in which he said, ``If your captors will permit me to come to
see you wherever you are, if it's physically possible for me, I
will come.''
   He said of the furor over his canceled west Beirut visit:
   ``I'm sorry that people feel that way ... If there are those who
are offended by my visit, I apologize to them. It was impossible
for me to do the things I would like to do.''
   Earlier Monday, O'Connor spoke with Hoss by telephone for 30
minutes.
   ``Hoss gave his views on the situation, and I listened very
respectfully and he listened very respectfully to mine,'' O'Connor
said, adding, ``It's not for me to determine a solution for
Lebanon.''
   Hoss later left for Damascus for talks with Syrian leaders on
Arab efforts to end the Lebanese crisis. Syria has 40,000 soldiers
in Lebanon under a 1976 peacekeeping mandate from the league, and
has been involved in an artillery war with the Christians that
began March 8.
   When reporters told the cardinal Hoss was a Sunni Moslem,
O'Connor said, ``I did not know that.''
   O'Connor was guest of Maronite Catholic Patriarch Nasrallah
Sfeir in Lebanon. He met Aoun for 1{ hours Sunday at the bunker of
the shell-battered presidential palace in Baabda east of Beirut.
   O'Connor declared complete support for Aoun's demands that the
Syrian army withdraw from Lebanon.
   At least 359 people have been killed in the artillery duels
between the 20,000 Christian troopers and an alliance of the
Syrians and Druse militiamen, which started two days after Aoun's
forces blockaded illegal ports run by Moslem militias.
   An Arab League summit in Morocco last week urged warring
factions in Lebanon to ``strictly adhere'' to a truce the league
proclaimed May 11.
   Syrian artillery positions in west Beirut continued firing at
the Christian coast north of the capital Monday, trying to keep
Aoun from bringing in arms and supplies by sea. Police reported no
casualties.
</TEXT>
