<FIRST>r i AM-Egypt-Libya     05-29 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Egypt-Libya,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Libya and Egypt Reopen Border</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The border between Egypt and Libya was
reopened Monday, Cairo's Middle East News Agency reported, but the
two countries have not restored diplomatic relations.
   The opening of the border followed a reconciliation meeting
between Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and Libyan leader Col.
Moammar Gadhafi during last week's Arab summit conference in
Morocco.
   It is expected that direct air service between Cairo and the
Libyan capital of Tripoli will be restored.
   The agency said the border was reopened at 10 p.m., and
officials in the border towns of Saloum and Mersa Matrouh were
preparing to open the land route that is used primarily by
Egyptians working in Libya.
   More than 200,000 Egyptians work in Libya. During the years the
border was closed they had to travel between the two countries by
way of Greece or some other third-nation transfer point.
   Libya and virtually all other Arab countries severed diplomatic
relations with Egypt after the late President Anwar Sadat signed a
peace treaty with Israel in March 1979.
   Most of the countries restored relations in recent years, but
hard-line Libya and Syria, along with war-divided Lebanon, have not.
   During the summit, which marked Egypt's return to the Arab
League, Mubarak held talks with Gadhafi and Syrian President Hafez
Assad but none gave any indication of plans to resume diplomatic
relations.
   Relations between Egypt and Libya have been strained since 1972
when Sadat, who was assassinated by Moslem exremists in October
1981, rejected a bid by Gadhafi to merge the two countries.
</TEXT>
