<FILEID>AP-NR-05-29-89 1954EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-MemorialDayRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0627 05-29 0776</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Memorial Day Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0627,0795</SECOND>
<HEAD>Day Of Remembrance For Some, Partying For Others</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with other activities, ADD quotes,
edit to tighten. No pickup. Georgian in 16th graf is cq</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos WX10; WX17</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER PETTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans on Monday remembered those who died for their country,
from wars long past to last month's explosion aboard the USS Iowa.
But many celebrated Memorial Day as the traditional start of
summer's sun and fun.
   ``I'm proud to be here. I wouldn't miss it. My son is gone 37
years and I've never missed a Memorial Day since I lost him,'' said
Emma Bosch, who was guest of honor at a parade in New York City.
Her 21-year-old son was killed in the Korean War.
   Hundreds of thousands of people hit the nation's beaches, and
while the weather cooperated over much of the country, it was
unseasonably cold in Montana, where Great Falls got 6 inches of
snow during the early morning.
   In a brief ceremony at Arlington National Cemetery, a 20-member
military honor guard laid a wreath at the grave of President
Kennedy to mark what would have been his 72nd birthday. No members
of the slain president's family attended.
   Later that morning, across the hilltop from where Kennedy is
buried, Vice President Dan Quayle placed the presidential wreath at
the Tomb of the Unknowns. President Bush was at a NATO meeting in
Brussels.
   Among the honored dead were some of the most recent: the 47
sailors who died April 19 aboard the USS Iowa in an explosion
inside one of the battleship's huge gun turrets. President Bush had
designated Memorial Day as a national day of remembrance for the
sailors.
   One ceremony for the Iowa sailors was held aboard the
decommissioned cruiser USS Little Rock, which is anchored on Lake
Erie at Buffalo, N.Y.
   The victims' names were read and when they reached Nathaniel C.
Jones, 21, of the Buffalo suburb of Tonawanda, his mother, Georgian
Davis, threw a carnation into the water.
   In California, a Civil War cannon boomed in Los Angeles and
police motorcycles roared in a solemn cavalcade in Oakland to honor
that state's dead.
   At the Los Angeles National Cemetery, which marks its 100th
anniversary this year, a restored Civil War cannon was rolled out
to fire a shot for the first time in decades.
   Veterans in Westwood, Mass., visited the grave of Robert Steele,
the drummer boy who at the age of 13 joined in the 1775 Battle of
Bunker Hill with the Dedham militia.
   ``He fought through the entire Revolutionary War, and in 1825,
when they built the Bunker Hill monument, he beat his drum again
when they dedicated the monument,'' said Jim Sullivan, director of
veterans services for Westwood, a town of 13,000 where 83
Revolutionary War veterans are buried.
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael S. Dukakis attended a ceremony at the
National Cemetery in Beaufort, S.C., to rebury the remains of 19
black Union soldiers. They were buried in a military cemetery in
the Union camp that apparently was neglected and forgotten after
the Civil War, and were found two years ago during road
construction.
   Ten airmen who died when their bomber crashed 10 days before the
D-Day invasion in 1944 were honored at a new memorial near their
crash site outside South Hadley, Mass.
   The memorial ``is all we can hope for, a warm place where the
butterflies play high up on the mountaintop,'' said Frank Tencza,
who organized the weekend ceremony and helped locate the soldiers'
remaining family members; more than 70 relatives attended.
   In Baltimore, about 3,500 people attended the dedication of a
monument to Vietnam veterans.
   A vandal threw white paint on Philadelphia's Vietnam Veterans
Memorial during the night. Early Monday morning, veterans who had
heard news accounts about the incident showed up with paint thinner
and scrapers to clean the monument before the ceremonies.
   A nonmilitary Memorial Day ceremony in Edmond, Okla., was no
less emotional. People cried when 14 jets of water were turned on
in a fountain built at the Edmond Post Office to memorialize 14
postal workers killed by gunman Patrick Henry Sherrill on Aug. 20,
1986. Sherrill later took his own life.
   After, or instead of, memorials, people headed to the beach or
park, or stoked up barbecues, to welcome summer.
   At Six Flags Over Georgia, the crowds were larger than last
year, said Bob Maxwell, park public relations manager.
   In Virginia Beach, Va., retired Soviet Maj. Gen. Valentin
Larionov watched the beach fill up with sun worshipers.
   ``This is real democracy,'' commented Larionov, part of a Soviet
delegation visiting the area.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
