<DOCNO> AP890529-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-29-89 2005EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-CancerCandor     05-29 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Cancer Candor,0612</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Court Says Patients Do Not Have Right to Know Disease</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI YAMAGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Patients do not have the right to be fully informed
of their disease by their doctor, a Japanese court ruled Monday in
the case of a woman who was told only that she had gallstones
before she died of cancer.
   The woman's husband immediately dismissed the decision by Nagoya
District Court as ``ridiculous'' and pledged to appeal it. The
ruling would not take effect nationwide unless the Supreme Court
upheld it, and appeals often take 10 years to reach the high court.
   Kazuko Makino, a 50-year-old nurse, died in 1983 of gallbladder
and liver cancer. Her doctor, Etsuro Orito of the Nagoya Second Red
Cross Hospital, found a tumor in her gallbladder but kept that
information from her and her family.
   Although Orito recommended surgery, Mrs. Makino decided against
it, believing she had gallstones. The hospital told the court Orito
was unsure if the tumor was malignant and therefore had no
responsibility to tell her she had cancer.
   Her husband, Ichiro Makino, sued the hospital for $342,000 in
damages. He said his wife would have agreed to an operation if she
had known her true condition.
   However, the court in Nagoya, 170 miles west of Tokyo, ruled
Monday that it is up to a doctor's discretion how much information
to divulge. The court said it was the patient's fault she did not
undergo the operation.
   ``Although a doctor has responsibility to explain to patients
about their diseases, it is the doctor who decides when, to whom,
and to what extent the explanation should be made,'' Chief Judge
Kuniharu Ito said.
   Makino said he would appeal to Nagoya High Court.
   ``It is doctors' ethics that I have been fighting for,'' Makino
said in an interview. ``Why didn't Dr. Orito at least tell us the
problem may have been something more serious, instead of telling us
lies?''
   In Japan, doctors generally give patients little information
about their diseases and often do not even tell them what medicine
they are taking.
   Doctors frequently do not tell patients when they have cancer,
believing it would destroy their will to live. Many Japanese
believe cancer is incurable.
   During the prolonged deterioration of Emperor Hirohito, the
government refused to confirm widespread reports that he was
suffering from cancer despite intense worldwide interest in his
condition. It was only after the 87-year-old monarch died on Jan. 7
that officials confirmed he died of cancer.
   In a survey in April by the nationally circulated newspaper
Asahi Shimbun, 60 percent of healthy Japanese said they wanted to
be told if they had cancer. However, only 20 percent said they
would tell relatives with the disease.
   Cancer, the No. 1 cause of death in Japan since 1981, claimed
206,000 lives last year.
   Hiroshi Horie, a surgeon at the Kyoto Prefectural University of
Medicine Hospital, supported the court's ruling.
   ``I've seen many patients who got worse after learning they had
cancer,'' he said. ``We doctors try to do only what is best for
patients, and so we don't tell them directly. Of course, we tell
their family _ that's a must,'' he said in a telephone interview.
   Tetsuo Kashiwagi, vice chairman of Osaka's Yodogawa Christian
Hospital, said doctors should be able to decide whether to tell
patients they have cancer, ``but they should respect patients'
right to decide what to do with their lives.''
   ``More doctors have come to tell patients the truth, and that's
the way it should be,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
