<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet 1stLd-Writethru a0607 05-29 0974</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0607,1000</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yeltsin Given Legislative Seat, Leads Victory March</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with victory parade details. Picks
up 4th graf, `Also on...' with minor editing to trim and conform</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos MOSB1,3,5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maverick communist Boris N. Yeltsin, defeated by
fellow deputies in a bid for the new Soviet legislature, was
suddenly handed a seat Monday and celebrated by leading a noisy
victory parade through central Moscow.
   In a parliamentary maneuver that had President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's blessing, a place was opened for the former Moscow
party boss when a winner in the elections to the full-time
legislature, the Supreme Soviet, resigned on condition that Yeltsin
take his place.
   An exuberant Yeltsin said the move indicated the Congress of
People's Deputies, which elected the members of the legislature,
``is gradually becoming more democratic. If it goes further along
this road, there is hope it will justify the hopes of the people.''
   A roaring and ecstatic mass of supporters surged upon Yeltsin
after he left the Congress. Well-wishers hung from trees and tossed
red roses.
   Yeltsin, smiling broadly, led a spontaneous one-hour march from
the Kremlin along Gorky Street to Pushkin Square, where about 5,000
people gathered. Women kissed him and men shook his hand.
   ``All the people are with you!,'' one man yelled.
   Yeltsin thanked the throng through a megaphone and ended the
rally with hands held high in a gesture of victory.
   Also on Monday, Gorbachev pushed his choice for vice president _
Anatoly I. Lukyanov _ through the Congress, but not before the
deputies subjected the little-known schoolmate of Gorbachev's to
tough questioning on his views and fitness for the job.
   The 2,250-seat Congress, empowered to elect the national
president from among its own members and to confirm the president's
choice of vice president, let Omsk University law professor Alexei
I. Kazannik vacate his spot in the bicameral Supreme Soviet in
order to have Yeltsin take his place.
   The decision, reached in minutes without a direct vote on
Yeltsin's candidacy, defused a tense situation that developed when
the outspoken opponent of official privilege finished last on a
list of 12 candidates for 11 Russian federation seats in the
legislature's Soviet of Nationalities in results announced Saturday.
   Tens of thousands of Muscovites chanting ``Shame!'' rallied
Sunday in a stadium parking lot to protest the defeat of Yeltsin
and other outspoken Moscow progressives running for the legislature.
   Leaflets circulated through the crowd proposed a one-hour strike
Thursday if Yeltsin were not named to some high post by the
Congress. State-run TV said Sunday a poll found 49 percent of
Soviets surveyed were unhappy with how the elections had been run.
   Yeltsin, the top vote-getter in March's popular elections for
the Congress, received 1,185 votes from fellow deputies for a seat
in the Supreme Soviet, while 964 voted against him. But he was
defeated by 11 other candidates, including Kazannik, who got more
votes than Yeltsin.
   Kazannik, a law professor, took the podium in the nationally
televised proceedings to offer to renounce his seat on condition
Yeltsin replace him without another round of voting.
   He said he could not return to Omsk as a legislator because the
Congress had failed to elect many prominent scientists and
politicians, including Yeltsin. ``I would be ashamed to face my
voters,'' said Kazannik, who is not a member of the Communist Party.
   Only a few deputies voted against a proposal by Victor Palm of
Estonia to allow Kazannik's resignation and his replacement by the
burly, white-haired Yeltsin, 58.
   ``Inasmuch as Comrade Yeltsin received a majority of the vote,
the open place can be filled by him,'' Gorbachev ruled from the
dais. ``Naturally, it does not require a repeat vote.''
   Gorbachev told Kazannik the Congress ``welcomed his initiative.''
   Yeltsin, stripped of his Moscow and Politburo posts after an
October 1987 speech criticizing the slow place of Gorbachev's
reforms, emerged from the Congress hall beaming with Kazannik at
his side.
   He said Muscovites, who gave him 89 percent of the vote in a
two-way race in March, would be ``partially satisfied.''
   On the march to Pushkin Square, a city bus stopped, and dozens
of passengers got off to join in.
   One Yeltsin supporter, Anna S. Sabalova, her eyes wet with
tears, declared joyfully: ``We knew he was a honest person. We knew
he was elected by millions, but that just a few in the Congress
held him back.''
   Even Yegor K. Ligachev, a Politburo member accused by Yeltsin of
impeding Gorbachev's drive for perestroika, praised the decision,
telling reporters: ``It was democratic'' and the right thing to do.
   Earlier Monday, Lukyanov underwent nearly four hours of
meandering questioning in which he was asked to explain his record
and views on issues ranging from fighting crime to the 1939
German-Soviet treaty that deeded control of Estonia, Latvia and
Lithuanian to the Kremlin.
   Gorbachev allowed the protracted questioning of Lukyanov, who
was first elected vice president by the Supreme Soviet in October,
but made it clear from the outset he wanted his handpicked deputy
confirmed without competing nominations from the floor.
   Gorbachev had tried for a vote on Lukyanov Saturday night but
gave in to loud objections from weary deputies who wanted more
discussion.
   The second time around, Gorbachev got what he wanted. Of the
2,250 deputies, only human rights activist Andrei D. Sakharov and
178 others voted against Lukyanov in a show of hands. There were
137 abstentions.
   Lukyanov, a student with Gorbachev at Moscow State University's
law school in the 1950s, has spent his career in the party and
government bureaucracy.
   Lukyanov takes over with other deputy chairmen of the Presidium
of the Supreme Soviet if the president cannot perform his duties.
He has no other constitutional duties but may be given assignments
by the president.
</TEXT>
