<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary-Reforms     05-29 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Reforms,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Politburo Member Says Communist Party Could Be Replaced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Politburo member Imre Pozsgay said the
ruling Communist Party could give way to a party based on Western
Europe's social democratic principles, Radio Free Europe reported.
   Pozsgay, considered the leading reformer in Hungary's Communist
Party, made the statement in an interview broadcast this weekend by
the radio's Hungarian program.
   Munich-based Radio Free Europe is a U.S.-financed network that
beams broadcasts to Soviet-bloc nations.
   Radio Free Europe provided English excerpts of the interview
that it said was conducted in Hungarian by one of the station's
correspondents who is based in Budapest. In March Hungary became
the first Warsaw Pact country to accredit a Radio Free Europe
journalist.
   The transcript provided to news organizations said Pozsgay was
asked if he would accept the position as the leader of a reform
Communist Party and quoted him as replying:
   ``I can say that such a party could not be called
reform-communist. That party would belong to the conceptual
framework of European socialism ....
   ``Only a party capable of adapting to the people and to the
European ideas could be effective and successful.''
   Pozsgay added, ``It would not be based on the communist
tradition of clinging to abstract ideas but rather on the type of
European socialist ideas that characterize the Italian or French
socialist parties or the Swedish, Austrian or West German social
democratic parties.''
   He was asked if communism is in a crisis and said, according to
the excerpts: ``This is a crisis of Stalinism. It has become quite
certain that Stalinism cannot be reformed because it has been a
failure, because it has become unsuitable for giving people the
experience and feeling of freedom.''
   He said Stalinism ``with its inclination for terror and violence
should be cleared away from the path because it does not correspond
either to socialism or to European political culture or to the
everyday needs of the people.''
   Pozsgay was referring to the years of rule by the late Soviet
dictator Josef Stalin.
   Hungary's Communist Party is undergoing major changes because of
the reform movement within the party.
   In February the party's Central Committee decided to accept
political pluralism.
   Legislative elections scheduled for 1990 will be the first since
the communist takeover in 1948 under a law that legalizes other
parties and will allow them to participate in the elections.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
