<FIRST>r a AM-Dean'sSchool     05-29 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dean's School,0459</SECOND>
<HEAD>James Dean's Hometown Trying To Save School Where He Got His Star</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAIRMOUNT, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The town where James Dean first sported
his trademark scowl still holds sharp memories for the actor's old
friends, who want to restore the abandoned high school where he
made his stage debut.
   So, fittingly enough, they're trying to raise money for the
91-year-old brick building with a 1950s-style sock hop and
cruise-in for hot rods.
   The school's ceiling is falling and the paint is peeling, but in
the gym Saturday night, the numbers on the scoreboard were shining
1949 for the year of Dean's high school graduation and 1955 for the
year he died in an automobile accident.
   ``This is kind of a do-or-die situation,'' said resident Ronald
Idlewine,'' who helps run the Madison-Grant Youth Basketball
League, which bought the school for $10 in 1986. ``Sure would be a
loss to see this stage go.
   ``Our first priority is to keep (the school) from falling down,
and to get that roof fixed,'' he said.
   Idlewine led visitors to the auditorium and to Adeline Nall's
speech room, where Dean learned how to project his voice, find
emotion in a line of script _ and to act.
   Ms. Nall, now 82, showed people around the room.
   ``This corner is James Dean's corner,'' she said. ``This is the
corner where he'd go whenever he came back to Fairmount. This was
after he was making movies. This corner has a lot of meaning for
me. He'd stand there waiting for class to end. ... Once he lit up a
cigarette.''
   Bob Pulley, who runs the Fairmount Historical Museum down the
street, remembered sharing the playbill with Dean in one of Ms.
Nall's productions.
   In 1948, Dean was a lead character in ``Our Hearts Were Young
and Gay,'' a comedy about a jaunt by two coeds aboard an ocean
liner to Europe. Pulley had a bit part as a steward.
   A year later, Dean wouldn't miss an opportunity to stand on his
school's stage. On Halloween, he dressed up like Frankenstein in a
spoof called ``Goon With The Wind.'' He was in the senior play,
``You Can't Take It With You.''
   And he placed first in the state speech contest with his
presentation of ``The Madman'' by Charles Dickens. It was sixth in
the national contest in Longmont, Colo.
   After graduation, Dean left Fairmount and headed for California,
where he made three movies over the next six years, ``Rebel Without
A Cause,'' ``Giant,'' and ``East of Eden.'' His death in a car
crash at the age of 24 gave him a lasting, almost mythic status as
a symbol of brooding youth.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
