<FIRST>u i AM-Argentina 3rdLd-Writethru a0663 05-29 0776</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0663,0804</SECOND>
<HEAD>State of Siege Follows Looting in Argentina, Suspends Rights</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 16 grafs to UPDATE with Menem's remarks. Pickup 14th
graf, `Government officials....' TRIMS thereafter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Raul Alfonsin declared a 30-day
national state of siege Monday night in an effort to stem a week of
looting touched off by economic chaos.
   During the day, thousands of looters rampaged through Buenos
Aires suburbs and Rosario, the country's third largest city. Many
were women and children trying to steal food from supermarkets.
   Police fired rubber bullets and tear gas to disperse mobs in
Rosario. One man was shot and killed, and at least 36 people were
wounded, police said.
   At least five policemen were beaten or injured by stones.
   About 600 looters were arrested in Rosario and 268 in
working-class suburbs of the capital, police said.
   The looting followed soaring inflation, rising unemployment, a
devalued currency, shrunken wages and national elections on May 14
that voted out the governing Radical Civil Union party.
   President-elect Carlos Menem, a Peronist, is scheduled to take
office Dec. 10.
   Menem quickly backed the state of seige. ``It's possible that
what happened in Rosario could be repeated ... in other places,''
he warned.
   He blamed unspecified agitators for the violence in Rosario.
   All constitutional liberties were suspended in the state of
siege, which takes effect immediately but must later be approved by
Congress. It was announced by presidential press secretary Jose
Ignacio Lopez.
   Both houses of Congress will review the action on Tuesday.
   Alfonsin also had declared a state of siege in June 1985 after a
wave of bombings blamed on right-wing extremists said to be out to
topple the government.
   Gov. Victor Reviglio of Santa Fe Province declared a state of
emergency in Rosario. Stores closed early, students were sent home
and classes were suspended. Nighttime entertainment was canceled.
Residents were told to stay indoors.
   Most of Argentina remained calm, however.
   Sackings of stores and clashes began in several cities last
Tuesday stemming from an economic crisis that began February.
   More than 120 food and clothing stores in seven cities and towns
have been raided. Homemade gasoline bombs were seized and about 870
people were arrested even before the latest flareup. The previous
clashes left at least 10 people injured by rubber bullets or tear
gas fired by police.
   Government officials blamed leftist agitators. They said looting
parties appeared to be organized, police communications were
disrupted by jamming signals, and carloads of young men were seen
carrying sawed-off shotguns.
   ``Without doubt, they are elements of the extreme left,'' Sante
Fe provincial minister Alberto Didier told the independent news
agency Diarios y Noticias.
   Spokesmen for the Communist Party and other leftist groups
blamed failed government economic policy.
   ``The reality is being demonstrated that hundreds of thousands
of people don't have anything to give their children to eat,'' said
national deputy Luis Zamora of the Movement toward Socialism.
   Pablo Davola, whose Rosario store was looted, agreed.
   ``I had a shotgun and prepared a system to electrify the doors,
but there were many people I knew, people from the neighborhood who
used to come and buy things. I didn't know what to do,'' he told
the independent news agency Noticias Argentinas.
   Economists and politicians say lame-duck President Alfonsin is
in a poor position to implement a recovery program he announced
Sunday night.
   Similar situations have led to military coups six times since
1930. Gen. Gen. Francisco Gassino, the army chief of staff, said in
a speech to soldiers Monday, ``We are not disposed to ... repeat
errors, although the gravity of the situation troubles our
spirits.''
   Since February, the austral currency has lost more than 90
percent of its value against the dollar. Inflation this month alone
may exceed 70 percent, which would be an annual rate of 58,162
percent.
   A Central Bank announcement said earlier Monday banks and
foreign exchange houses that were closed or restricted May 22 would
resume normal operations Tuesday.
   Alfonsin sent Congress tax and spending measures aimed at
stabilizing the economy. Other measures he mentioned in a
nationwide address Sunday night took effect by decree, including
free subway passes for students and senior citizens.
   He pledged to reduce the budget deficit by cutting spending on
capital projects, increasing export taxes and enforcing income tax
laws, raising fees for public services and selling state-owned
radio and television stations.
   He also promised to enforce price guidelines.
   Real wages have fallen by 30 percent since January, according to
the Latin America Research Foundation, and are at the lowest level
since Alfonsin took office in December 1983.
</TEXT>
