<FIRST>r a AM-PipelineExplosion 1stLd-Writethru a0677 05-29 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pipeline Explosion, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0677,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Residents Begin Returning to Homes Affected in Pipeline Explosion</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 4th graf, ```I have...,' to UPDATE with
number of families returning; raises penultimate graf to 6th graf to conform.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN BERNARDINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some of the 270 residents forced
to flee after a pipeline explosion killed two people began
returning to their devastated neighborhood Monday but were warned:
``Enter at your own risk.''
   Many other residents were reluctant to return to the grim site,
where two weeks earlier a runaway train derailed, killing three
people and demolishing a row of homes.
   Investigators are focusing on the possibility that the train
wreck damaged the pressurized pipeline, ultimately causing the
explosion.
   ``I have a handicapped child. How can we live in a home where we
can't guarantee his safety ... or our own for that matter?,'' said
Ed Cisneros, 46.
   About 30 of the approximately 170 families evacuated, totaling
some 270 people, were given permission to return home Monday,
police Officer John Montecino said. By late Monday, only 13 of the
30 families returned to the stricken area.
   Those who did were met by signs posted throughout the
neighborhood warning: ``Enter at your own risk, City of San
Bernardino.''
   Also Monday, city officials and owners of the 14-inch pipeline,
which exploded last Thursday, negotiated conditions to reopen the
line.
   Calnev Pipe Line Co.'s parent company announced over the weekend
the damaged pipeline would be rebuilt under tougher standards, but
would remain in the same location.
   Representatives of the pipeline owner, Chicago-based GATX
Terminals Inc., met for two hours Monday with Southern Pacific
railroad officials and city negotiators, said City Attorney James
Penman.
   ``We basically explained that we want the line moved west of the
railroad tracks'' and away from the houses that were destroyed or
endangered, Penman said.
   The pipeline owners have balked at moving the line, saying such
it would be shut down for too long.
   ``The pipeline is very critical to the national defense
system,'' said Robert Claypoole, president of GATX Terminals. He
said fuel from the line flows to Air Force bases in California and
Nevada.
   U.S. District Judge David Williams signed a temporary
restraining order barring the city from interfering with
replacement of the line, which carries gasoline from Southern
California to Las Vegas. Meanwhile, gasoline is being trucked to
the desert gaming resort city.
   Penman said the city would go to San Bernardino Superior Court
on Tuesday, seeking a temporary restraining order of its own to
keep Calnev from reopening the line.
   Calnev officials declared the pipeline safe following the train
wreck, and Claypoole said the refurbished line would be ``extremely
safe.''
</TEXT>
