<DOCNO> AP890529-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-29-89 2350EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Plane-Lake     05-29 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plane-Lake,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>Diving Instructor Pulls Man From Submerged Plane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A diving instructor on a tourist-jammed
lake gave a real-life lesson in rescue skills when he repeatedly
plunged into 25 feet of water to save the pilot of a small plane
that crashed minutes before.
   The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers estimated that up to 165,000
people were on Bull Shoals Lake near the Missouri border when the
incident occurred during the Memorial Day weekend, but no other
injuries were reported.
   Scores of witnesses saw the single-engine plane crash Sunday
afternoon. The diving instructor, John Van Der Voorn, 42, with no
gear other than a borrowed diving mask, went down three times
before pulling Mark Seemeyer, 35, out of the cockpit of the plane.
   ``I teach a specialty rescue class,'' Van Der Voorn said Monday
as he and his wife packed to return home. ``I did exactly what I
taught. I never thought I would use it.''
   Seemeyer, of Fenton, Mo., was upgraded from critical to stable
condition Monday, according to a nursing supervisor at Cox South
Hospital in Springfield, Mo.
   A passenger in the plane, Mike Kuhn, 33, of Sunset Hills, Mo.,
floated to the top after the crash, but Seemeyer, who was
unconscious, was buckled into his seat, Van Der Voorn said.
   Kuhn was also in stable condition Monday night, the spokeswoman
said.
   Van Der Voorn, who was supervising about 25 students on a diving
trip sponsored by his shop in Morton, Ill., said he was in a cove
``on a knee board ready to ski'' when the plane went down about 300
yards behind him.
   He said he heard a boom and looked behind him just in time to
see the plane plummet into the water. Van Der Voorn said he climbed
quickly into the ski boat and was at the crash site within two
minutes.
   ``My wife and I dove in,'' Van Der Voorn said.
   ``The first time I couldn't get down because I had a wet suit on
and I was too buoyant,'' Van Der Voorn said. ``On the second dive,
I found the man unconscious, leaning forward. I found a seatbelt
around his knees,'' he said.
   Van Der Voorn said he got the seatbelt off and he thought an
unidentified diver who had joined in the effort was pulling
Seemeyer up.
   ``When I got to the top he said he didn't have him, that he
couldn't hold his breath that long, so I went back down,'' he said.
   By then, Seemeyer had settled back into the seat. ``I got him
and pulled him up,'' the diver said. He immediately began giving
mouth-to-mouth resuscitation.
   ``That diver happened to be at the right place at the right
time,'' said Rick McCloskey, chief of a sheriff's diving team that
patrols the lake. ``If it wasn't for him, the man would have been
dead at the scene.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
