<FILEID>AP-NR-05-29-89 1930EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Nissan-GE     05-29 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nissan-GE,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nissan, GE Capital To Launch Auto Maintenance Venture in Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nissan Motor Co., Japan's second-largest carmaker,
said Monday it will join GE Capital, a major U.S. finance company,
in launching a corporate automobile fleet maintenance company in
Japan.
   It will be the first such business to be undertaken by a company
in Japan, said a Nissan official who spoke anonymously.
   Nissan said the service will be started through a business
tie-up with Stamford, Conn.-based GE Capital, a division of the
General Electric Co. The Nissan official said other details had yet
to be finalized.
   The Nihon Keizai Shimbun, a major Japanese economic newspaper,
said the joint venture, scheduled to start business in July, will
be owned about 50 percent by Nissan, 30 percent by GE Capital and
20 percent by six Japanese commercial banks.
   In the fleet service business, an agent handles a variety of
jobs necessary to maintain cars owned by companies, including
regular inspections, repair and refueling.
   GE Capital has about 20 years of fleet service experience,
handling about 440,000 vehicles in the United States, the Nihon
Keizai Shimbun said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
