   The Federal Communications Commission has
approved the $18 billion merger of Time Inc. and Warner
Communications Inc., removing the last federal regulatory hurdle to
the creation of the world's largest entertainment and media
conglomerate.
   Both companies welcomed the FCC decision, announced late Friday.
The proposed conglomerate, Time-Warner Inc., would surpass Rupert
Murdoch's Australia News Corp. as the world's biggest media and
entertaiment concern.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Mercantile Exchange and the Chicago
Board of Trade have agreed to try to unify their planned
after-hours electronic trading systems.
   Their announcement Friday marked a turnaround for the Board of
Trade, which had been highly critical of the Merc's planned Globex
system and last fall recommended that the federal government deny
the Merc permission to operate it.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Renewed declines in interest rates provided the fuel for a broad
pre-holiday rally in the stock market Friday. The Dow Jones average
of 30 industrials rose 11.18 points to 2,493.77, cutting its loss
for the week to 7.33 points.
   The dollar finished mixed in choppy domestic trading after
falling overseas. Gold prices fell after trading mixed overseas.
   Bond prices advanced.
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mostly lower; energy
futures were higher; precious metals were lower; and livestock and
meat prices were down.
